\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil left the cafe pleased with himself. He'd learned something, and it had made the case more intricate and therefore more interesting, and also more breakable. The more ways in, the better. He drove over to the sheriff's office and found John Kraus, a tall, portly bald man who wore the department uniform, and looked like a cook, or a potential department-store Santa.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Got your files right down the hall," Kraus said. "We got them either on computer, or on paper, but I got you the paper ones. Easier to shuffle things around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's terrific. Just the way I like it," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Kraus said, "I'll leave you to it. We got some coffee going down the hall, to the right. Can's around the corner."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil started by calling Bell Wood, an agent with the Iowa Division of Criminal Investigation. "Tell him his personal hero is calling from Minnesota," Virgil told the woman who answered the phone.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wood came up: "That fuckin' Flowers. Everything was going so well, too. Just a minute ago, I told Janice, everything's going too well-something's wrong."\par
