\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Things are getting very strange, and very complicated," Virgil said. "We need to ask you something: do you know whether or not Bobby was acquainted with, or dating, a young woman, a girl from the west end of the county, named Kelly Baker?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Irma: "Baker? Wasn't that the girl who was murdered?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. Last year, down by Estherville," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You can't think that Bobby had anything to do with that," George Tripp said, anger threading back into his voice.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, no, we don't," Virgil said. "But we're wondering if Jacob Flood might have."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The Tripps stared at him for a moment, then Irma Tripp rocked back on the couch and said, "Ohhh. Oh, no. You think Bobby found out about… Ohhh."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did they know each other?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The two looked at each other, and then George Tripp said, "Our son, you know, never really had much to do with girls, yet. He was shy. But there was something going on a year ago. We don't know with who, because he wouldn't talk about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He didn't take anybody to the junior prom," Irma Tripp said. "We kept trying to get him to take Nancy Anderson, she's really a nice girl, and we'd hoped… Do you think he was seeing this other girl? Kelly?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She lived out in the countryside," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He was always borrowing the car, soon as he got his license," George Tripp said. "That wouldn't have been a problem."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She worked at the Dairy Queen here in Homestead, during the summers," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There you go," George Tripp said. "The Dairy Queen's a regular meeting place for the kids. He would have been down there most every day, at one time or another."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So there's a possibility he could have known her, but you don't know that specifically," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Irma's head bobbed. "That would be it. But now that you bring it up, I think he must have known her. He was so strange last fall. He grew up a cheerful, outgoing kid…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Got a football scholarship, over in your hometown," George Tripp said to Virgil.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I heard that," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "… but last fall, he was so gloomy," Irma continued. "We thought maybe the football team, it didn't do as well as people hoped. We thought he was down about that. But if…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We would like to look through his private things… anything would help," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What would you look for?" Irma asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Any indication that he had prior contact with Flood, with Baker, with Crocker, any notes or letters…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, I don't know," she said, turning to her husband.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Probably the best thing would be to have agent Flowers look," George Tripp said. He said to Coakley, "I know you were doing your duty, Lee, but I gotta say… if you hadn't taken him… if your men were up to standard… he'd still be alive. I think I'd prefer it if you didn't come back here. Not unless you have to."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley bobbed her head and said, "I know what you're saying, George, and I'm so sorry. But Virgil would do a fine job, as good as anybody in the state. He's one of their top men."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So let's do that," George Tripp said. "Not right now. Irma and I have to… do things. If we get our boy back tomorrow…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There's a time problem," Virgil said. "How about if I give you my cell number, and you call me when you're okay with it. Tonight or tomorrow. There is the time thing. We've got at least one murderer running loose, and probably more."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 George Tripp nodded. "We can do that."\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 5\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Pat Sullivan, the newspaper reporter, covered cops and everything else in town, and had been calling the sheriff's office on a fifteen-minute schedule since the rumors of Crocker's death began to leak out. Coakley called him back, with Virgil sitting next to her desk.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "Pat? Lee Coakley. You called?" She listened for a minute, then said, "Why don't you walk over? We've got a state investigator here and we can fill you in." A few more words from the reporter, and she said, "See you then," and hung up.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 To Virgil: "He's on his way."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good guy?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, for a reporter," she said. "He's accurate, usually, but he's ambitious. The editor tells me his friend-his relationship, his guy-lives up in the Cities. He'd like to get up there with the Pioneer Press or the Star Tribune."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Fat chance," Virgil said. "Those places are bleeding to death. Bet there are a hundred good reporters looking for jobs."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You know them?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A few," Virgil said. "And they talk about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You think they'll be down here? For these murders?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "May get some TV," Virgil said. "The newspapers, you're more likely to get a call. I mean, they could have a staff meeting in a phone booth."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They sat for a minute, looking past each other, then Coakley asked, "You at the Holiday?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They looked past each other some more, until Virgil asked, "You didn't mention to Sullivan that we wanted to talk to him about Tripp."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I thought I'd leave that to you. Best to ask him first, before we get to Crocker. That way, we're holding the Crocker information over his head. Or, you are. I'm just a humble county sheriff, who has to defer to the state agent, if he decides to screw over the local media." She leaned back in her chair, turned, put her boots up on top of a wastebasket, put her hands behind her head, and stared at the ceiling. She did it in a comfortably coordinated way, which made Virgil think it was her regular thinking posture. "I have two possibilities."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Only two?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, there are several more, but two I'm thinking about. One: Flood and Crocker were friends, which we know, and that Crocker killed Bobby out of simple revenge. Two: Crocker killed Bobby because he was afraid that when Bobby told us why he killed Flood, that it'd come back on Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They considered that for a moment, then Virgil said, "Crocker didn't kill Tripp until early morning, almost time for a shift change. I wonder why he waited? I wonder if he needed to talk to somebody about it? Like your other woman. We oughta check the phones here, see if he called anyone during the overnight. And check his cell."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We can do that," she said. Another moment, and she asked, "You cook? Or you eat out?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm not much interested in food," Virgil said. "I mostly eat microwave. Healthy Choice, like that. Cereal. Milk. Scrambled eggs."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "My husband used to cook, a lot, when I was married," Coakley said. "I used to work some odd hours. Now, I get home in time to cook, most nights, but can't get it going again. The boys are happy with pizza and burgers and fries, but I feel guilty about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How many kids you got?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Three. Sixteen, fourteen, and twelve," she said. "The twelve was supposed to be a girl. So was the fourteen, for that matter. All I got is a bunch of big lugs. Though I love them to death."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sounds like you kept busy for a while. Three kids in four years."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, well. Going to Mankato State, got married halfway through my senior year. I was knocked up by Memorial Day," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What'd your husband do?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He's the new car sales manager over at Gable Ford," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Still see him?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, no. The new wife wouldn't like it, for one thing," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh-oh."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What can I tell you? He got married three weeks after our divorce was final," she said. "I guess it had been going on for a while. Never saw it coming."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She have really big breasts?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The thin smile again. "Ample. Or ample-and-a-half."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Give her any speeding tickets?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hadn't thought of it, but now that you mention it, I'll keep it in mind," she said. Her phone rang, and she picked it up, listened, and said, "Send him in."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Pat Sullivan was a short, thin man, of the sort that Virgil thought of as "weedy." He had brown hair, a prominent nose, a brush mustache, and square Teddy Roosevelt teeth. He wore brown boots with studded soles, was carrying a parka and a reporter's notebook.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil Flowers," he said, when Coakley introduced him. "I've followed your adventures. That shoot-out up in International Falls, with the Vietnamese dragon lady. The one out by Bluestem, with the federal guys."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They're like bad dreams slowly fading away," Virgil said. He pointed at a chair: "Sit down. We gotta talk. There's more going on than a story."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan sat down, a skeptical look on his face: "Like what?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We have to go off the record for a bit," Virgil said. "That good with you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Depends. We can start that way. If I can't keep it off, I'll tell you," Sullivan said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When Bob Tripp was arrested, he wouldn't talk to the sheriff until he talked to you first," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan's eyebrows went up. "Me?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. Are we off the record?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. For now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We wondered if you knew what he might have wanted to talk about," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So you didn't ask me to come in as a reporter, but as a possible witness."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil shrugged: "I don't care if you're both. Not a problem for me."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan said, "I'll have to think about it… but if Bobby wanted to talk, why would he have committed suicide?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "He didn't. He was murdered. Probably by Jim Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Whoa." Sullivan went pale, leaned forward. "This has got to be on the record. Not about Bobby wanting to talk to me, but about Bobby and Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We'll come back to it, give you a formal interview, on the record. Let's stay off for now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan paused, then nodded.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Crocker isn't a sure thing, for Bobby's murder," Virgil said. "I can think of scenarios where he didn't do it-but we think he probably did. We may have more definitive answers after the investigation."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley jumped in, pressing the question, "Do you have any idea why Bobby might have wanted to talk to you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan leaned back, looked at Coakley, then Virgil, then back at Coakley. "Lee, I assume you know that I'm gay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I knew that," she said, nodding.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I cover a lot of sports. People around town had heard I was gay, and some of the high school kids knew about it. Maybe most of them. Anyway, I interviewed Bobby a few times, he was a star. Then, one time, he asked me if he could stop by my apartment and chat. I said, 'Sure,'" Sullivan said. "By that time, I had an idea of what was coming. Anyway, he came over, and beat around the bush for a while, then said that he'd heard that I was gay, and that he was worried that he might be, and he just wanted to talk about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Was he?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, sure. As far as I know, he hadn't been sexually involved with anybody-including me, we never were-but he had already gone through most of the self-recognition stuff," Sullivan said. "You know, feeling this strong attraction toward some of his teammates, and he'd fantasize about them, instead of the girls in his class, and all the rest-checking out the scene on the Internet, maybe checking some gay porn."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did he ever mention Jacob Flood to you?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan shook his head: "No. When I heard that Bobby was dead, and that he'd been arrested in the Flood case, I was amazed. We talked quite a bit, and he never mentioned Flood's name."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil: "And nothing about Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not a thing. Not even during the election."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know if Flood or Crocker were active in the local Homestead gay culture? There must be a few more gay people here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan nodded. "Quite a few," he said. "Maybe a hundred, or more? But not all of them are active around here, and I've never heard of those two. That doesn't mean much, though-it's not like we all hook up. I know maybe… a dozen gay people here? Something like that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did Bobby ever mention a girl named Kelly Baker?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan, who'd been slumping in the chair, straightened, and tipped an index finger at Virgil: "Now her, we did talk about. Is she involved in this deal?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Wait," Virgil said. "You say you talked about her. Did he know her?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, yeah. He met her at the Dairy Queen. He used to give her a ride home, sometimes. I think he was hoping that he might, you know, get involved with her, find out that he really wasn't gay. It didn't work out that way. I think… I think-he didn't actually tell me-that she picked up on the fact that he was gay. Didn't bother her, and they became friends."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The Iowa people didn't talk to him? The cops?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not as far as I know. I mean, Bobby and Kelly were a summertime thing, when the Dairy Queen was open. After school started, she was gone, and then, you know, she was killed. He didn't know anything, and they never really had a relationship, so… it just went away, I guess."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Doesn't help much," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let me ask a question," Sullivan said. "Have you actually checked on Flood's sexual orientation?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not yet, but it's on the list," Coakley said. "We know he was married, but we also know that whoever killed Kelly Baker was into some extreme sexual behavior. Homosexuality might fit in there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Doesn't seem all that extreme to me," Sullivan said. "Homosexuality."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You don't know the details," Virgil said. "But here's the thing that hangs me up. Bobby wanted to talk to you. Not his father, or one of his pals. So, I have the feeling that you would already know something about what he wanted to talk about, and that most likely would have to do with sex. You say it's not Crocker, not Flood, so it has to be Kelly Baker. But why would he want to talk to you about Baker?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know," Sullivan said. "Maybe because I knew about the situation between them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He never said anything to you about Baker being involved in… extreme sexual situations?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan let a grin show: "That's the second time you guys have used the phrase… I'm starting to get interested. But no. He never mentioned anything like that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Damnit. I was hoping for magic," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let's go back on the record, so I can get a few questions in," Sullivan said, flipping open his notebook.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Talk to Lee," Virgil said. "I've got to make some phone calls before it gets too late."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to say that you were called in to work the case," Sullivan said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's fine. Refer to me as the affable, good-looking, outdoorsy blond guy," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "With a serious line of bullshit," Coakley added. VIRGIL CALLED Jacob Flood's home number, got a woman who said she was his daughter, and who said, "Mother's out. She'll be back at supper time."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Does she have a cell phone?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. I can give her a message."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil identified himself and said that he'd like to come over after supper. He left his cell phone number and asked for a call-back if Alma Flood wouldn't be there.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called the duty officer in St. Paul, learned that Beatrice Sawyer and Don Baldwin had the crime-scene van and should be at Crocker's place. He called Sawyer, a cheerful middle-aged woman, who, Virgil thought, was sometimes a little too interested in death.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Got here half an hour ago and had a look, eyeballin' it," Sawyer said. "It's murder, all right. Tell you something else-the sun went down, and it's dark as the inside of a horse's ass out here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're sure?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I've never actually been inside a horse's ass."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "About the murder?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We feel that after the slug penetrated his lower jaw, tongue, roof of his mouth, sinus passages, eye socket, brain, and skull, he probably wouldn't have had time to wipe the gun, or any interest in doing so," Sawyer said. "But the gun was wiped. With a cotton blouse, we think. A couple threads got caught in the action. Ergo…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. So he wasn't alone," Virgil said. "You saw his penis? Exposed?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. We believe he was involved in heterosexual activity immediately prior to his demise. Whether he actually ejaculated we won't know until the autopsy is done, but we have no signs of semen on his clothing or the couch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There was a suggestion here, by the sheriff, that he may have been involved in oral sex," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That would be accurate," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil was surprised that she was so positive. "Really?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. Because that explains the lipstick on his penis," she said. "That's also why we think it was heterosexual, and a blouse was involved in the gun-wiping. We could be wrong, but we rarely are."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Bea… you're my huckleberry."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, you say that to everybody," she said. "If it was oral sex, we have the possibility of getting some DNA. I won't go into the details of how we plan to collect it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thank you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But we will be doing that. I'll tell you, Virgil, there might not be much more. This shag carpet, this fuzzy couch, there was a blanket… it's an old house, and there's a lot of dirt around. The furnace has been blowing dust on everything. It's going to be a chemical mess. Our best hope is the DNA on his penis, and we'll check the fly of his pants."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're also looking for a pair of uniform pants, green wool, with blood on them," Virgil said. "Could be a very small amount, but you've got to find them. Check every pair of green wool uniform pants you can find. The blood comes from a ripped fingernail, so there might not be much. We'll need DNA on that, too."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If it's there, we'll get it," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Bea…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Don't say it," she said. "The huckleberry thing. Once was annoying enough." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On his way back down the hall to Coakley's office, Virgil got a local call, from a number he didn't recognize. He answered, and found Bob Tripp's father on the other end. "I've talked to my wife, and we're going over to the funeral home tonight at seven-thirty. If you wanted to get here at seven twenty-five, we could put you up in Bob's room by yourself. We'd just as soon not be here when you go through it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll see you then," Virgil said. "Thank you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley was alone when Virgil got to her office. She had her boots back on the wastebasket, and was staring out her office window. When Virgil stuck his head in, she pointed at a visitor's chair.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Look a little bummed," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I am."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We'll get this cleared up, you'll be the town heroine," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Three murders," she said. "And probably four. You know the last thing I did before I got elected sheriff? My last investigation? I was looking for some kid who was going around keying trucks."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Catch him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, but I know who did it," she said. "I got myself close to the little asshole's father, down at the diner, in the next booth. I was having lunch with the chief, and I said, 'There's gonna be trouble when I catch this kid. He's done fifty thousand dollars' worth of damage, and the insurance companies will be after him or his parents with a chain saw.' That stopped it, you betcha."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, that's good," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But you never did car-keying investigations," she said. "And I can tell you, you can flat get whiplash from the change in speed, from car-keying to quadruple murder."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Never did a car-keying investigation, but I once investigated the theft of toddlers' pants," Virgil said. He told her about it, and they exchanged a few more stories, and Virgil told her about the phone calls, and finally she sighed and said, "It's supper time. You should get out to Flood's, and I'm going home to cook some… crap. Macaroni and cheese. I can't stand to think about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So take some time, cook something good. Think about the case while you're doing it. Call me when you think of something."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She poked a finger at him. "And you call me. Tonight. I want to hear about Flood, and about Bob Tripp's room. Tonight."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They walked out to the parking lot together, and then Coakley said, a frown on her face, "By the way, when we were talking to Pat, you said you could think of a few scenarios where Crocker didn't kill Bobby. So what're the scenarios?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil shrugged. "Crocker is having an affair with a female deputy, who came in to shut up Bobby. She kills him, while Crocker is off someplace, doing something. Gets her pants scratched. But she's worried that Crocker is going to tell somebody that she was there-use her for an alibi, if somebody finds out Bobby was murdered. And maybe she knows enough about autopsies to know that we might find out. So she goes over to Crocker's and kills him to shut him up, before he can tell anyone that she was at the jail."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, goddamnit, Virgil, you're coming back on me again," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, I'm not," Virgil said. "I was just thinking of scenarios. Besides…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Besides, what?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Bobby was a star athlete," Virgil said. "I don't think you're strong enough to keep him pinned long enough to strangle him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ahh… Go away."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You gonna think about it?" Virgil asked. "The scenario?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll think about it, but it's bullshit," she said, and Virgil went away. VIRGIL GOT to the Flood house well past dark, but could tell the house was a big one, a cube, white clapboard around the first floor, dark brown shingles around the second floor and the attic level. It sat squarely facing the county highway, on a low rise a hundred yards back, with a shelterbelt of fir trees to the northwest and west, dark against the Milky Way. Five snowmobiles were rolling down the ditch to Virgil's left as he came to the Floods' driveway, and they went bucketing on past into the night.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The yard was illuminated by three lights-one over a side door to the house, a yard light on a pole by the corner of the house, and another on a pole by the barn. The barn and a couple of lower outbuildings, a garage and a machine shed, sat off to the right of the drive, with the glint of a silvery propane tank off to the left. No cars were visible in the yard lights: everything was buttoned up, and dark.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil could see no tracks going to the front porch as he came up the drive; not unusual. The side door would be the main entry. He climbed out of the truck, took a second to look around, and to feel the cold night air on his face, and to look at the stars, then walked to the side door and rang the bell.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He could hear a thumping inside, somebody running. A moment later, the door popped open. Two teenage girls stood looking at him, in the dim light of a small overhead bulb, and he nodded and said, "I'm Virgil Flowers," and one said, "Yes, we were waiting," and the other, "Come in. Wipe your boots."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I could take the boots off."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No need. Nobody else does."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The girls appeared to be about twelve and fourteen, junior high school age. They were dressed almost identically, in dark blue jumpers with white blouses and black tights, with black lace-up shoes. They were sallow with winter, with deep shadows under their eyes: their father had been murdered.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked, "So, what are your names?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm Edna," said the older one, and the younger one said, "Helen."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He followed them up four stairs into a kitchen and around a corner and through another door into a living room. One of the girls called ahead, "Mother, Mr. Flowers is here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Alma Flood was sitting on a couch in a book-lined living room, a reading lamp over her shoulder, a Bible on the arm of her chair. A man, older, big, farm-weathered with a white beard, a big red nose, and small black eyes, sat facing her on a recliner chair. A glassed-in bookcase, built under the stairs going up to the second floor, was full of what looked like fifty-year-old novels, the kind you'd find in a used-book store or an aging North Woods resort.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Alma Flood was square in the body, as the girls would be, with her hair pulled into a bun; she wore a dark brown dress. There was a resemblance between her and the older man, and Virgil thought he might be Alma Flood's father. She said, "Mr. Flowers. You have news?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe," Virgil said, smiling. The man gestured at the second recliner in the group of furniture, and Virgil sat down. A comfortable chair, and the house looked prosperous; but no sign of a television set. Virgil said, "You know the sheriff arrested Bob Tripp for Mr. Flood's murder. Bob Tripp was then killed in jail-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I thought he committed suicide," the older man said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, in his polite voice, "I'm sorry, who are you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Emmett Einstadt. I'm Alma's father."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay… An autopsy was done on Tripp, and the medical examiner believes that he was murdered."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's nonsense," Einstadt snapped. "We were told by the sheriff herself that there was nobody there but Jim Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded. "That's correct. The autopsy turned up indications that Tripp may have been killed by Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, no, that's not possible. Jim Crocker is a righteous man," Alma Flood said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When we went to talk to Deputy Crocker this afternoon, we found him dead at his house. He'd also been murdered."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They were astonished. Not faking it at all, as far as Virgil could tell. Alma's hands went to the sides of her head: "Jim Crocker is dead?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Somebody shot him," Virgil said. "There are indications that it may have been a woman." VIRGIL GOT ALONG okay with animals-dogs, horses, chickens-but his relationships with them were nothing special. Cats were different. For some reason, which he didn't entirely understand, cats liked him.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He'd come from a cat family, of course, and that might have had something to do with it. They'd supported numerous cats over the years, ranging from the conservative red tabby Luther to the radical black Savonarola, with a dozen in between, all named for religious figures by Virgil's minister father. Now a cat walked into the Floods' living room and sniffed at him, and Virgil reached out a hand.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Alma Flood and Einstadt exchanged exclamations about Crocker-"Can you believe that? How could that happen? What's going on?"-and then Edna Flood said to Virgil, about the cat, "Don't try to pet her. She'll bite your fingers off."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded and pulled his hand back, and he gave them a short summary of the findings at Crocker's place, then asked, "Do you know any reason Jim Crocker would want to… take revenge on Tripp, because of what happened to Mr. Flood?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, they were friends all their lives," Einstadt said. "If they weren't hanging around here when they were kids, they were hanging around the Crocker place. Started rabbit hunting together when they were ten, when we gave them their first.22s."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So there might be something," Virgil suggested.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There might be, but I can't see Jim killing because of that. He'd let the law take its course," Einstadt said. "If justice didn't get done, then he might… well, as a matter of fact, I doubt he'd do anything. He wasn't that kind."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The cat sniffed Virgil's pant leg, then hopped up on the arm of the chair, sniffed his ear, and then crawled up on his shoulders and settled down behind his neck. He could hear her purring.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's the darnedest thing I've seen in years," Helen Flood said, as though she were forty.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil reached back and scratched the cat under the ear, and asked, "Did any of you know, or did Mr. Flood know, a girl named Kelly Baker, who was killed a year or so ago down by Estherville? She came from down south of here, a few miles…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Flood and Einstadt looked at each other, and then both shook their heads. "We know them," Einstadt said. "They belong to the same church we do. But we don't know them well. We're not close. We know about what happened to Kelly Baker, of course. Everybody was talking about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Alma Flood asked, "Do you think they are connected? Kelly Baker and what happened to Jacob? That the Tripp boy did it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil had been considering the possibility, but hadn't worked through it until Alma's question clocked a new scenario into place: what if Tripp and some other kids had been using Baker, and Flood found out? What if Tripp had confessed to Crocker, and Crocker had killed him because of some relationship between himself and the Baker family? And that the other person involved in the murder of Baker had killed Crocker…\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 But that didn't work well: Crocker had been involved with a woman. Could there have been some kind of teenage sex ring, that included females, and something went wrong with Kelly Baker? But why wouldn't Crocker simply have alerted the sheriff, rather than murdering Tripp?\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 There was no logic to it-though that didn't always mean much. But Virgil shook his head at Alma Flood and said, "No, we can't make that work. Although Tripp did know Kelly Baker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then you've got one boy you know for sure is a cold-blooded killer, who killed Jake. And he knew another girl who was killed, somehow. I won't tell you how to do your business, but that looks like a solid connection to me," Einstadt said. "How many murderers do we got in this county, anyway? Looks to me like the Tripp boy and one of his friends might have been up to something here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Another scenario flashed: suppose Kelly Baker had been gay, and they had a three- or four-way thing going, involving the other woman? Too far-fetched…\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, we'll sure look into it," Virgil said. "Like I said, we think Crocker was murdered. We'll know for sure soon enough, and we'll probably get some DNA from the killer." The cat made a snogging sound behind his ear, and he reached back and scratched her again.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked for a while longer, but on the central issue-what Jacob Flood might have known, or said, that triggered his murder-they came up empty. "I'd never heard of this Tripp boy before we were told that they arrested him," Alma Flood said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When they were done, Virgil stood up and said, "I may come back, if I find more questions. I'm not familiar with this corner of the county. But if you talk to your acquaintances around here, you might ask if anybody knows of a connection between Deputy Crocker and Kelly Baker. Or Crocker and Tripp, for that matter."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We'll do it," Einstadt said. "We're just buckling down for winter, so we'll be coming and going-we'll see a few folks."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil gave them a business card, carefully removed the cat from his shoulders, scratched her head, and put her back on the floor. "I appreciate all your help," he said. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When he was gone, Einstadt looked at Alma Flood and said, "You know who killed Crocker?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was thinking Kathleen."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was thinking the same thing," he said. "I'll get Morgan and we'll go have a talk with her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He stood up and said, "Rooney will be over tomorrow."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Alma Flood whined, "We can get along all right. We don't need Rooney."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Rooney's a good man and you'll knock some edges off him. The thing about it is, you leave a bunch of women alone in a house like this, you can't tell what they'll get up to. Rooney'll handle that, and take care of the farm, too."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He's rougher'n a cob," Alma Flood said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Like I said: you'll knock some edges off him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Be happy if he took a bath," Alma Flood muttered.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll tell him that," Einstadt said. He looked at the two girls, standing in a corner. "You girls get your asses upstairs. I'll be up in a minute."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 One of them said, "Yes, Grandpa," the other one said nothing, and they both headed for the stairs.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt said to his daughter, "When Rooney gets here tomorrow, I want you to make him welcome. I don't want any trouble about this. But-don't tell anyone that he's moving in. That's private business."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He turned away and followed the girls toward the stairs. He hadn't had any sex for two days, and he needed it, and the last time he'd bent Alma over the kitchen table, she'd been dry as a stick.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The girls, though…\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He left Alma sitting in her chair, with her Bible, and hurried up the stairs, the hunger upon him.\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 6\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The Floods were unusual, Virgil thought, as he drove away. Reticent. The daughters looked morose, as might be expected, but had never mentioned their father. Neither had Alma Flood or Emmett Einstadt, except in direct discussion. There was no hand-wringing or remembrance or tears: they spoke of him almost as though he were a distant acquaintance.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt looked like an Old Testament image of Abraham, as he was about to stick the knife in Isaac's neck. And the way they dressed, all brown, black, and blue-he didn't know if this was a religious thing, similar to the plain dress of the Amish, or personal preference.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Back at Homestead, Virgil took the exit, looked at his watch: coming up on seven o'clock, not enough time to eat before he had to be at the Tripps'. He stopped at a convenience store, got a bottle of orange juice, a pack of pink Hostess Sno Balls, and a couple of hunting magazines to take back to the motel.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 One of the problems with working in a small town was that whenever you went somewhere, you were already there-it was only six or eight or ten minutes from one end to the other, so if you were running early, you stayed early, and if you were running late, there was no way to make it up by speeding or taking shortcuts.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He stopped a block from the Tripps', parked, ate the Sno Balls and drank the juice, and watched a man walking along the dark street with two Labrador retrievers. The dogs were looking for a comfortable snowbank in which to take a dump; the product of their efforts would sink into the snow, and freeze, and in March, when the snow went away, there it'd be. Sometimes, if your yard was on a popular corner, whole piles of newly thawed dog poop ushered in the spring.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil thought about the unfairness of it, and checked his watch. Still early, but not too; he stuffed the juice bottle and Sno Ball packaging in a trash bag hung from the back of the passenger seat, and went on down the block. THE TRIPPS HAD GOTTEN dressed up for their visit to the funeral home. George Tripp was wearing a church suit, black wool with a white shirt and black-and-blue tie, and Irma was wearing a black dress with black boots with low heels. They looked simply, ineffably, sad.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 George Tripp was standing in front of the picture window again, waiting for him, and opened the door when he came up the walk. "Come in, please," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Irma Tripp came into the living room, carrying a long coat. She said, "We haven't gone into his room except once, to make his bed. It's just… too much."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did you figure anything out?" George Tripp asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We did learn one thing-your son did know Kelly Baker," Virgil said. "We know that for sure. They hung around together the summer before last, but probably stopped seeing each other when the summer ended. We don't think they were intimate, but, of course, we really don't know, one way or the other."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Crocker killed them both," George Tripp said. "Or Flood killed the Baker girl, maybe with Crocker. Is that what you think?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's a possibility," Virgil said. "But I just talked to Flood's wife, and they turn it around from that-they think your son killed Baker, and Flood found out something, so Bobby killed him." They both objected, and Virgil held up his hands: "I'm just sayin'. I will tell you that I'm not buying any theories, yet. But we know that we have at least one killer running around loose, and that's the thread we've got to pull on."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You don't have any idea who he is?" Irma Tripp asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, we're pretty sure it's not a he. We think it's a woman," Virgil said. "Somebody who was intimate with Deputy Crocker. We're pushing that aspect of it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If you look hard enough, you'll find out that Bobby comes out okay," George Tripp said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's why I want to look at his room," Virgil said. "Maybe there's something. Maybe he left a letter or a note or something that would explain this to us."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Bob Tripp's bedroom was at the far end of the house, in the front corner. The bed was neatly made-Irma went in and made it after he was killed, as though it were a final favor-but the rest of the room was about as messy as any teenage boy's might be. Books and papers were scattered over a desk, where a MacBook sat in front of an old-fashioned wooden office chair. A backpack lay at the foot of the bed, and a sports trophy, with a tennis player on top, stood on a chest of drawers. There were none of the expected jocko pennants on the wall, but there were posters for the Minnesota Vikings and New Orleans Saints, a couple of dozen postcards, mostly of nude women, stuck on the wall with pushpins. The place smelled faintly of sweat socks and male deodorant.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Irma said, "Those postcards aren't anything-those dumb boys would find them and mail them to their friends with, you know, messages, on the back. Trying to embarrass each other. They were all doing it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We'll just leave you," George Tripp said. "We don't want to see any of this, to be honest. And we have our appointment, you know, we have to pick out…" He trailed off, and Virgil mentally filled it in: a coffin.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Take off," Virgil said. "I'll wait until you get back."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They left him, but then Virgil stepped into the hallway and asked, "Did he have a cell phone?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes, it's on his desk."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. You don't know if he had a password on his computer, do you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Irma smiled for the first time, an almost shy smile, and she said, "Yes, he did, and he wouldn't tell us what it was. He said it was his private business. You know, I think with what boys look at on the Internet… We have wireless."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. I may want to take the computer with me," Virgil said. "We have some people in St. Paul who can work around the password."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 George Tripp said, "I don't know how valuable it might be…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll get it back to you," Virgil said. "I'll give you a receipt. You go on-we'll work it out later." HE WENT to the computer first, and the first thing it did was ask for a password. He tried "Tripp" and "BJ" and "Bobby" and "RJ," "Irma," and "George," and, from a school poster taped to the wall, "Cardinals" and "Vikings," "wide receiver" and "receiver." Nothing worked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He checked the phone and came up with a list of names and phone numbers. He recognized "Sullivan," the reporter, but the rest meant nothing to him. No Baker, Flood, or Crocker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The phone would have to be run. He set it aside and turned to the room, starting with the chest of drawers. He pulled each drawer three-quarters of the way out, felt through the underwear and summer clothing, then pulled each drawer completely free to look under it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Under the bottom drawer he found a plastic baggie containing a couple of joints and a package of rolling papers. He thought about it for a moment, then put the dope and the papers in his pocket.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Going to the closet, he shook down all the clothing, looking for paper, found a few gasoline receipts. Nothing in the shoes.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On impulse, he went back to the computer and typed in "gay" and "homosexual" and "homo" and the computer shook him off. He lifted the mattress off the box springs, found nothing. He went through the desk drawer, found it stuffed with receipts, ticket stubs, photographs. Nothing that set off a buzz.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He started sifting through papers and books, looking for anything that might be personal. Not much-no notes from anyone, just old schoolwork. The backpack contained workout clothes and two twenty-pound weights, probably to work his quads, and a printed-out calendar with a workout schedule on it, over the background image of a running horse, its tail flaring out behind it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And a much-folded piece of copy paper, with a line drawing of the Statue of Liberty on it. No words, just the drawing. There was a long oval drawn from the base of the statue right up to its face, which might have been the number "eight" but, if so, heavily distorted, with the upper loop nearly round, the lower loop a very long oval. The distortion seemed to mean something, Virgil thought, but he couldn't think what-but it looked as though the paper had been something that Tripp had looked at over and over, and carried with him on his daily workouts.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil looked at the statue drawing, then the calendar with the horse, went back to the computer, typed "Mustangs"-the Southwest Minnesota State Mustangs, where Tripp would have gone to college-and the computer bit: he was in.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Excellent," he said to himself, as the Mac started to load.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He found 776 incoming e-mail messages and 538 outgoing. He clicked on the "From" queue to alphabetize the incoming messages, and found twenty-two from KBaker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Nothing from a Crocker or a Flood.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 With the sense that he was on to something, he began paging through the KBaker mail, noting the dates. The e-mail began in June of the summer before last, and rather than ending at the end of the summer, continued through the autumn, with the final KBaker note coming two days before Baker was killed.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 As he went through the mail, his sense of anticipation dwindled: the exchanges were letters between teenagers, about when Baker would be in town, about who was dating whom, about summer jobs, about football. Baker was apparently religious: she mentioned a couple of times that she couldn't come to town because she had to go to church that night: the nights included Tuesday and Friday.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Three interesting notes from Baker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The first: "Definite stud muffin."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The second: "I wish I could go with you. If I was in high school, it'd almost be like I was normal. You're about the only outside person that I know, who knows how lonely this can be."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The third: "Can't: Got Liberty."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The third note was the last e-mail from Baker, the one just before she was killed. He looked for antecedents to the two notes, either from Baker or Tripp, and found nothing. They were like remnants of oral conversations.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The e-mail, as a whole, had a curious flatness to it: no flirtation, nothing in the least controversial. Something, he thought, was missing-and he suspected that Tripp had cleaned it up. The "definite stud muffin" message struck Virgil as a reply to something-and possibly a hint that Baker knew that Tripp was gay, and was commenting on some previous e-mail about somebody Tripp was attracted to.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Can't: Got Liberty." There was that paper in the backpack with the Statue of Liberty drawing on it. A connection? But to what? Or who? Was the capitalized word "Liberty" a proper noun, a specific person or place?\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Could the computer guys recover the deleted mail? Have to try.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He looked through all the rest of the mail, scanning quickly, and most of it was the same as the mail to and from Kelly: meet me there, let's do this or that, going up to the MOA with my folks. MOA was Mall of America, in the Twin Cities.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Huh.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He went to Safari, the browser, and clicked on "History," and came up empty-not a single entry. He checked the settings and found that Tripp had set the browser to erase his website visits on a daily basis.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He went to the "Security" icon, clicked on it, and found that the computer was set to accept cookies from the sites Tripp visited. He clicked on "Show Cookies" and came up with a list that ran into the hundreds of items. Scanning down the list, he found a lot of what appeared to be sports sites and, from the names, what appeared to be gay porno sites.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 All right, he knew that.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A thought popped into his head. What if Flood had somehow discovered that Tripp was gay, had ridiculed him, or challenged him-or even solicited him-and Tripp had lashed out purely in anger, with no other connection to anything?\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 No: Tripp had taken the T-ball bat from home. He'd gone to work prepared to kill Flood.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Besides, there were too many dead people for something that simple.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And where in the hell did a woman fit in, a killer?\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil continued working the room, no longer expecting to find much: Tripp had been covering himself. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The Tripps were back in a little under an hour, and Virgil was done with the room, sitting on the bed, looking around, wondering what he'd missed. He heard them come in, sighed, stood up, picked up the cell phone and the computer, and walked down the hall to meet them.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Find anything?" George Tripp asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know-I will have to take the computer. Your son was e-mailing back and forth with Kelly Baker, right up until the time she was killed. They were pretty friendly…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You figured out the password?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Mustangs," Virgil said, and George Tripp showed the tiniest of smiles.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How friendly were they?" Irma asked. She asked in a way, Virgil thought, that solicited a response that Bobby Tripp and Kelly Baker were in bed together. Because, Virgil realized, Irma knew or suspected that her son was gay.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Friendly. I can't say more than that, but there's no feel of… violence in it," Virgil said. "Of potential violence. At this point, I really don't believe your son was involved in hurting her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Of course he wasn't," George Tripp said. "It was that goddamn Flood, or Crocker, or both of them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to look into that," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He asked them to go through the contact list on Tripp's phone; standing together, they did that, and identified each of the people on the list, including Sullivan, who, they said, had interviewed their son a half-dozen times.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Everybody knew Bobby was going to be a college star. He could've gone to the Gophers, but they wanted to make a corner-back out of him and he didn't want that," George said. Wistful, now, with a glint of tears in his eyes: "He was going to be something." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On his way to the motel, Virgil threw the joints out the window-they were biodegradable-and crumbled the Ziploc bag into the trash. No need for Tripp's parents to know about that.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called Coakley from the motel, told her about the search, about the relationship with Baker, and about the "Liberty" note.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good: sounds like you're getting somewhere," she said. "I set up meetings with both of the female deputies for tomorrow morning. You're not invited. I've been thinking about them since I left the office, and I already know they're not involved. I'll push them anyway, which means my popularity is going to take a hit, but I'll do it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You've got four years-I think pushing them now will be pretty small potatoes when you break these murders," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When I get done, to show that I trust them, I'm sending all of them out to the countryside around Battenberg, to talk to folks," Coakley said. "The community out there is so sparse that somebody must know who Crocker was sleeping with-people know each other's cars, and even if it was just seeing a car parked in his driveway, somebody knows."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. I want to talk to Kelly Baker's parents. There's something going on there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "See you tomorrow," she said. HE MADE a late check with Bea Sawyer: "We got the pants," she said. "We can see a snag and what could be blood, and from what you said, I believe it is. So does Don. There's enough blood for a DNA check, so we'll be able to nail that down for you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Excellent. When will you be done?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We've already shipped the body up to Ike in Mankato," Sawyer said. "We're going through the house now, but we're about to quit. We'll be back tomorrow."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You at the Holiday?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nah, we're staying at a little ma-and-pa place in Battenberg. Pretty handy," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. I'll see you out there tomorrow. Try not to destroy any evidence."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called Coakley back: "Got a piece of information for you: the crime-scene guys have a pair of uniform pants at Crocker's, with a snag and a smear of blood. Probably Tripp's, I expect."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good. That really does take my other people out of it," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Pretty much," Virgil agreed. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Two inches of snow fell overnight, kicked out of an Alberta Clipper that swung down through the state and just as quickly departed. Virgil could hear the winds coming up as he went to bed, and then the muffling effect of the snow.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He thought about God for a while, and the early and traumatic end of expectations: Bobby Tripp "would have been something," his father said, and those expectations were now gone and might never have existed.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And he thought about the commonality of comfort, stretching back over the centuries and millennia, a guy lying alone in a warm space, listening to a clipper just outside the cave, igloo, hut, teepee, motel, whatever, a long thread reaching all the way back to the apes.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Then he went to sleep. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 In the morning, he'd just gotten out of the shower when his cell phone rang, and Coakley said, "Why don't we hook up at the Yellow Dog? Get some pancakes."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Half an hour," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He got dressed, checked e-mail, packed up his computer, and put on his parka. The clipper had slipped away, and the day would be sunny but cold: he brushed the light, fluffy snow off the truck and, by the time he was done, could feel the sharp near-zero temps on his cheekbones.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He pulled into the cafe just as Coakley did, and she asked, as she got out of her truck, "Any more ideas?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think you had the best one-go out to Battenberg and stir around, see what happens."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They went inside, got a booth, peeled off their parkas. Coakley was wearing a plaid wool shirt over a black turtleneck, with just a hint of lipstick. They discovered a common interest in blueberry pancakes and link sausages, and after they ordered, she said, "Kelly Baker-it has to be local. I mean, local-local. Here, not Estherville, not Iowa."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Close to here," Virgil agreed. "The killers weren't travelers."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The pancakes arrived with the cafe owner, who introduced himself as Bill Jacoby, and asked if there was anything new in the case. "Maybe," Virgil said. "We think whoever killed Deputy Crocker was a woman, and we're looking around for whoever may have had an ongoing sexual relationship with him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He was killed by somebody he was sleeping with?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We think so," Virgil said. There were a couple of dozen people in the cafe, and the nearby tables had gone quiet. "We're kind of looking around for someone who knows who that might be."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I don't," Jacoby said. "Be an interesting thing to know, though."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And something else," Virgil said. "You know that Kelly Baker girl who was killed down by Estherville a year ago? We think that murder is tied into the new ones."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Really," Jacoby said. "Man, that's freaky. That's a lot of dead people."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure is. We're looking for all the connections we can find," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A grizzled, rancher-looking guy in the booth behind Coakley said, "You know, you should talk to Son Wood. He used to hang around with Crocker, some, and they go back a ways. He might know who Crocker was going with."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil leaned sideways so he could see the guy past Coakley: "Son Wood. S-O-N? Where's he at?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He's got Son Wood's Surface Sealers out on 15 South," the rancher-guy said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley said, with a little razor in her voice, "Virgil, eat your pancakes. They're getting cold."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Hey. I'm just trying to be a friendly guy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Come in anytime for a cup of coffee," Jacoby said. "We don't have doughnuts, but we got twelve kinds of pie."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll do that," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When Jacoby had gone, Coakley leaned into the table and said, "What? You're a talk-show host?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He said, "What good does it do to keep the information private? The killers know everything we do. Why shouldn't the taxpayers know it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "Well." Thought about it, then said, "It doesn't seem law enforcement-like."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's a problem for law enforcement," Virgil said. "You can get a lot more done if you ask around, and spread the joy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm still a little annoyed," she said. "Sitting here in a cafe, blabbing to every Tom, Dick, and Harry."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Your eyes sparkle when you're annoyed," he said, giving her his second-best cowboy grin. His first-best grin was so powerful that he reserved it for places where the woman had her back against something, for support; like a mattress.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "For God's sakes, Virgil, try to keep your mind on what you're doing…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Slender, yet firm body," Virgil said, wiggling his eyebrows at her.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She showed some teeth. "I'm gonna stick this pancake up your nose, in about one minute."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. All right," he said, holding up his hands, palms out. "I'll suppress my feelings, if you say so. You're the sheriff."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to talk to the girls, then send them out to Battenberg. I'll go with them. I've got John Kraus talking to that list of kids on Bobby's phone. What are you doing?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I developed one solid lead since last night," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Really?" Her eyebrows popped up.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. There's a guy named Son Wood on Highway 15 South who hung out with Crocker, and who might know what women he was hanging with. I'm gonna talk to him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then, I'm going to go talk to Kelly Baker's parents."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good. That's a plan. Maybe I'll meet you there-I've never talked to them, myself." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They finished their pancakes under the eyes of the cafe patrons, Virgil telling her about the strangeness of the Floods, and about this and that. Coakley looked at her watch and took a last hit of her coffee and said, "Call me."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She left, and Virgil watched her go. Slender, yet firm body. And she gave him a hard time, but she sort of liked it. It was, Virgil thought, drifting toward the philosophical, a truism that no woman was really upset when somebody suggested she was attractive.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jacoby came over with a carafe: "More coffee?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thanks, Bill-maybe a half cup."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Anything more that Lee didn't want us to know?" Jacoby asked as he poured.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, not really, not much that wasn't in the paper this morning. We know the Tripp boy killed Flood, and now we know that Deputy Crocker killed Tripp. We've got that nailed down with DNA, and I expect we'll get some DNA off Crocker's body, from the woman, so if we can find her, we'll nail that down, too."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "DNA from the woman-what, like a hair? Blood?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Saliva traces," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jacoby leaned forward and dropped his voice. "Saliva? How'd you know where to look?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Crocker was… his dick was sticking out," Virgil said, pitching his voice down below Jacoby's.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You mean…?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I do."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, jeez. Maybe I ought to try to find her before you do," Jacoby said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Think about it, Bill. What happened to Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jacoby scratched once, in the general area of his groin, and muttered, "Might be worth it. I'm so goddamn horny the crack of dawn ain't safe."\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 7\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil hadn't known exactly what a surface sealer did, but when he found the small dealership and showroom, he discovered that Son Wood used a variety of paintlike substances to seal concrete or wood floors from whatever might get poured on them-like cow or pig urine, gasoline or oil, or grease.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 An auburn-haired woman was sitting behind the reception counter, typing into a computer screen and, when Virgil walked in, took off her reading glasses and asked, "Are you Harvey?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nope. I'm Virgil. Flowers. I'm an agent for the state Bureau of Criminal Apprehension, looking into your murders. Is Mr. Wood around?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, yes, he's in the back, talking to Roger. Can I tell him what it's about? Specifically?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He was a friend of Jim Crocker's, and we're talking to all of Crocker's friends."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That was just terrible," she said. "Let me get him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wood came out a moment later, followed by the woman. He was a tall man, thin, weathered, with flinty blue eyes and a three-day beard. He was wearing a red flannel shirt and pipe-stem jeans, and cowboy boots. He and Virgil shook hands and Virgil said, "We've been interviewing people around town, and a couple have mentioned that you knew Deputy Crocker. We know that he'd been intimate with a woman shortly before he died, and we'd really like to talk to her. Do you have any ideas?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, you know, I don't," Wood said. "As a matter of fact, I can tell you right out front that I'm surprised there was a woman with him, because he never seemed that much interested."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "In women?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, not so much women… as any particular woman." Wood scratched his head, just above his left ear, and said, "I don't know how to put it. He was interested in women, okay? He was married for a while, but I never knew him to date. You see what I'm saying? He didn't seem interested in particular women. He didn't go out with anyone."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Would there have been any takers?" Virgil asked. "If he started looking?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, yeah. There's not a big surplus of women around here, but he had a good job. You know how it is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded. "So you guys hung out, had a few beers…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That was pretty much it. We'd go fishing a couple times a year," Wood said. "We weren't all that close. I'm married and he's single… but, yeah, we go back a way."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Can you think of anything…?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, you know he was tight with Jake Flood. They knew each other since they were kids. There must be something in there… something in that whole mess. Jake getting killed, then Jim."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "That's what we think, too. We're looking for the connection."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe you ought to talk to his ex-wife," Wood suggested. "She's over in Jackson, her name's Kathleen Spooner. Kate. Changed her name back to her maiden name after they broke up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Bitter breakup?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well-no. He told me he didn't know what the hell happened. He came home one day, and she said she was moving on, that she'd filed for divorce that day at the courthouse, and did he want pork chops for dinner, or meat loaf?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The woman chipped in: "I talked to her for a minute, downtown, and she said she just got tired of his act. She said she didn't much want to marry him in the first place, and she'd been right."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So she just went on down the road," Wood said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You know if he went for the meat loaf?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "More of a pork chop man," Wood said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked for a few more minutes, but nothing else came up-Wood didn't know Kelly Baker or any of her family. "I know where they're at, but they ran a pretty small grain operation, and that doesn't need my product so much."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know anything about the religion he belonged to?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Just that it was a little unusual," Wood said. "He didn't talk about it that much, and he didn't go to services much. But some."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I thought they stayed pretty much to themselves."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Some of them do, some of them don't so much," Wood said. "I never exactly figured them out, because, to tell the truth, I wasn't much interested. But they're not like the Amish. I've been in some of their houses, and they have TVs and stereos and computers and so on. They're not so much for fancy cars-Fords and Chevys, mostly. But they do buy the Star Wars farm equipment. They got money." VIRGIL GAVE HIM a card, and walked out to the truck. He'd just gotten in and started it when Wood came out of the front of the showroom, jogging toward the truck, his shoulders up against the cold. He pointed at the passenger seat, and Virgil popped the door and Wood climbed in.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I didn't want to say a couple things in front of Delores, because she's a good bookkeeper, but the woman does tend to run her mouth. This all might be nothing, and I don't want to get good people in trouble, because of a bunch of rumors."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They won't be in trouble, if they didn't do anything," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wood shook his head and said, "Okay: Every few years I'm out at the Flood place. They run a hundred head of Charolais up there, grass-fed stuff for the specialty stores, and they've got some winter feeding platforms that I coat… Anyway, I was up there a couple of years ago, and I made some comment to Jim about how religious the Floods were. He was a little loaded and he said, "Yeah, really religious, but that don't keep them from fuckin' like a bunch of goats."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wood paused, put his hands over the warm air registers on the dashboard, then said, "The thing is, he said it in a way like there was something weird about it. Then he shut up. When I asked him about it the next time I saw him, he said he couldn't remember saying anything like that, but I could see he did. Like he was keeping a secret. He really seemed to want to walk away from what he said."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So what was weird?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Just his… voice. And then his attitude. Not scared, exactly, but like there was some dark secret. About the religion, I think. So-for what it's worth."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But you really don't know about the religion."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, I don't. There are a lot of little different ones scattered around here, mostly, you know, Bible-thumpers of one sort or another. There's quite a few Muslims around now, immigrants, and there's even a rabbi or two over at the slaughterhouse-that's what I understand, anyway." He shook his head again, and added, "Anyway, I thought I should mention it, because it seems odd, and because both Jim and Jake Flood have been murdered."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Glad you did. If anything else pops into your head, give me a ring. Whoever did all this is dangerous, and we need to get him off the road."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wood nodded and said, "The other thing that I didn't want Delores to hear, is that Jim was seeing his ex every once in a while. He didn't even want me to know that, I think, but it came out a couple times. They weren't talking about getting back together, but they were… you know, whatever the kids call it: hooking up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Thanks for that, too. Stay in touch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll do that," Wood said, and he popped the door and ran back through the cold to his shop.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil made a note to talk to Crocker's ex-wife as soon as he could, and eased out onto the highway. As soon as he got going, he called Coakley; she had finished talking to the women, was sending them out to Battenberg to knock on doors.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going out to the Bakers' place. You want to go out in your truck, or you want to ride along with me?" he asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. Why don't I meet you there? I might need my truck later on."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tell me how to get there…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She gave him some simple directions, said, "That's not the shortest way, but it's the easiest, you won't get lost-and it'll let me catch up to you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "See you there. Before you come out, run Jacob Flood through the NCIC, see if you get a hit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Already did that-no hits."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "See you at Bakers'."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The trip out took half an hour, the countryside not quite flat, but rather a series of broken planes, now a frozen wash of gentle blues and grays with the new snow. Virgil had read once that Grandma Moses was a primitive painter because she thought snow was white. The writer said if you really looked at it, snow was hardly ever white. It mostly was a gentler version of the color of the sky-blue, gray, orange in the evenings and mornings, often with purple shadows. When he looked, sure enough, the guy was right, and Grandma Moses had her head up her ass.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On the way over, he called a researcher named Sandy at the BCA and asked her to find Kathleen Spooner, called Kate, formerly called Kathleen Crocker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If she's still in Minnesota, I'll get it in a minute or two," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Text it to me so I'll have a record."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Like most of the farmhouses around, the Baker place sat facing a county highway, a hundred yards back, perched on a rise with a windbreak of box elders and cottonwoods to the northwest. Virgil slowed to check the name on the mailbox and saw Coakley's truck coming up from behind. He waited on the side of the road, and she slowed, and pointed, and he followed her up the freshly plowed driveway to the house. On the way up the drive, his cell phone burped: a text message. He looked at the screen and found an address and a phone number for Kathleen Spooner.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Out of the truck, Coakley said, "I called ahead. They're both here, and waiting. They've got a boy, he's off studying wind power at Minnesota West in Canby."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Would he be Bobby Tripp's age?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Her eyes narrowed: "I think… he might be three or four years older. We can ask."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They were walking up to the side door of the farmhouse, and Virgil filled her in on the conversation with Son Wood, and added, "I'll try to find Crocker's ex-wife this afternoon."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Worth a try," she said. "She's been gone for a while, though. Five or six years, I guess."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But Wood thinks they may have been back sleeping together," Virgil said. "That's interesting. A familiar female."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We could use some DNA…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The Bakers were as different as grapes and gravel; Leonard Baker had yellowish-red hair that flopped over one side of his head, so that if it had been black, it would have looked like Hitler's haircut. He had a pointed chin and a pointed nose, and freckles all over his face and hands.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When he nodded and smiled at them, a formal smile, as they followed him through the door, Virgil saw that he was missing one of his upper eyeteeth; and a moment later, picked up a periodic whistle that came through the empty space when Leonard said a word that began with a "W."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Louise Baker was raven-haired and black-eyed; not pretty, but noticeable. She wore a formless dress, with a tiny red-dotted floral design, that fell to her ankles, and she was not, Virgil thought, wearing anything beneath it. Like, nothing-but what was under there was definitely of an interesting quality.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Leonard Baker said, "If I understand this right, Miz Coakley thinks that our daughter's death might be mixed up with this murder at the elevator? Then we heard that Jim Crocker got killed, and that maybe a woman did it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's what we think," Virgil agreed.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But whoever killed my daughter, they were men," Baker said. "That's what the Iowa folks said."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's probably right," Virgil said. "But we've discovered that a boy named Bobby Tripp murdered Jacob Flood, and then that Tripp was murdered by Deputy Crocker. And that Bobby Tripp was a friend of your daughter's. A good friend."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Louise was silent but Leonard Baker said, "Well, that's not right. I would have known about something like that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley said, "Not intimate friends… they didn't have a personal relationship. They were friends. They talked to each other, e-mailed each other."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I keep a pretty sharp eye on that computer," Baker said. Then, "But I suppose once they learn how to use it… we're not here all the time."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And there are computers everywhere," Coakley said. "Libraries, schools…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We homeschooled," Louise Baker said. Her voice was crinkly, like when a sheet of vellum is crumpled in a hand. "Leonard taught her mathematics and German, and I taught her English and literature, and we both taught her religion."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil caught what seemed to be an irritated look pass from Leonard to his wife when she mentioned religion, and he jumped on it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If you don't mind my asking, what religion? I'm a preacher's son," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We have a personal and private religion," Leonard Baker said. "We really don't talk about it to nonmembers."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay," Virgil said, and then quickly, following up, "Bible-based? Or…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Leonard Baker nodded: "Yes. We're followers… well, yes. The Bible."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "I haven't had a chance to review all the investigation from Iowa, but I know the outlines of your daughter's case. The Iowa people say that you had no idea of what had happened with Kelly. Have you had any thoughts since that time? Has anything come up?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The couple looked at each other, then simultaneously shook their heads. "We are mystified. The police said… well, that Kelly was sexually active."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That was ridiculous," Louise Baker said. "When could she be?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley: "You let young girls work in town, things happen. They grow up so fast now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We didn't even know that she had male friends her own age, like this boy you're talking about," Leonard Baker said. "That she was not a virgin when she was killed-that doesn't seem possible to us. The time factor… when could she have gotten out? She did work, summers, but she was a quiet girl."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's a mystery," Louise Baker said, her voice crackling with what might have been stress.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know somebody named Liberty?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The two looked at each other again, and Virgil had a sudden intuition: they knew, and they'd lie about it. They turned back to Virgil and both shook their heads. "No. Nobody named Liberty."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They said they knew who the Floods were, but weren't really acquainted, and they did know Crocker. "He was a righteous man," Louise Baker said. "He patrolled out here, before he was assigned in town, so everybody knew him. I suppose… no offense, Sheriff… I suppose most people out here voted for him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Leonard Baker nodded: "If he killed the Tripp boy, it was for a reason. The Tripp boy must belong to a gang. If he knew Kelly, then I think you've taken a big step in finding out who killed her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think your son might have known Tripp?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Leonard Baker shook his head: "I don't think so. He never worked in town. He was homeschooled, too, both of them were. When he graduated, two years ago, he got a job in Blue Earth, so he never was around Homestead. And then he went off to study wind power."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked for a while longer, and Louise Baker asked if they should be afraid for their own lives: "There're killers out there, and they've already taken Kelly from us. What if they're crazy people?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If you don't know what's going on, then I think you're safe," Virgil answered. "There's a thread that links all this together, and if you're not pulling on the thread, then you should be okay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Louise shivered: "I'm still scared."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "At times like this, you need to be strong and courageous. Don't be afraid or terrified; we're with you," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They nodded, and Leonard Baker said, "Just… mystified. Mystified."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Back outside, Coakley said, "That wasn't a lot of help. But they're also pointing us back to Tripp. Maybe there's something-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They were lying through their fuckin' teeth," Virgil said. "The Bakers know something and they're scared. That probably means they know something about their daughter's death, and they're hiding it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What'd they lie about?" Coakley asked. "I missed it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Louise said Crocker was a righteous man. Mrs. Flood said the same thing, the same words, but they deny that they know each other. Bullshit. They know each other and they've been talking. And this Bible thing, the righteousness thing. Mrs. Flood had a Bible, and now the Bakers say they belong to a Bible-based religion, and they're pretty serious about telling you that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So I threw a little Deuteronomy thirty-one:six at them, one of the most famous verses in the Bible. They had no idea," Virgil said. "Be strong and courageous. Do not be afraid or terrified because of them, for the Lord your God goes with you; he will never leave you nor forsake you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well-just because they're Bible-based, doesn't mean they know every word," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They should know those words," Virgil said. "There's something going on here, out in the countryside, and we don't know what it is, do we, Mrs. Jones?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "My: from the Holy Bible to Bob Dylan. I'm impressed," she said. "Did you notice that Louise was a little spare on the clothing?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I noticed," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I noticed you noticing," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She didn't look prim, she didn't look controlled, like a fundamentalist usually does. She looked a little out there, in a morose kind of way," Virgil said. He smiled at Coakley. "There's something going on, and that makes me happy. Second day on the case and we've got something. We need to think about the Bakers and the Floods. About their religion. Something going on, Lee."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What's next?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil looked at his watch: he had time. "I've got Kathleen Spooner's address over in Jackson. I'm going to run over and talk to her," he said. "If I have the time, I might check with Junior Baker up in Canby… though that might have to wait. That's a ride."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to check back with my girls up in Battenberg," Coakley said. "Stay in touch."\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 8\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Kathleen Spooner had her back to the wall-the front room wall-facing off the three men who'd shown up unannounced as she took her lunch break. Emmett Einstadt, flanked by two younger men, all three farmers, dressed rough in work coats and pants and boots, tracking dirty snow across her floor.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, keeping her voice low, controlled, "I don't know what you're talking about, Emmett. I heard Jim was killed, and I felt bad about it for one minute, but I had nothing to do with it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You two were going at it, the last pool," Einstadt said. "They says it was a woman who done it, and he wasn't going with nobody else."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Old times' sake," Spooner said. She was an average-sized woman, a little heavy, but not too, with dark hair and eyes. She wore a University of Minnesota fleece, dark slacks, and a touch of red lipstick. "Besides, everybody else was taken up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But we thought about who else it might be, and we can't think of nobody," said Wally Rooney. "The thing we know is, that nobody else knows, is that you're crazier than a bucket of frogs. It didn't bother you one little bit to put a bullet through his head."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And you got the guns," said Ted Morgan.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Killed with his own gun, is what I heard. It could have been suicide," Spooner said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt glanced at the other two, then said, "You know what? I keep my ear to the ground, and I haven't heard it was his own gun. Nobody told me that. Anybody tell you boys that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The other two men shook their heads, and Morgan said, "Nobody told me."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What I want to know, more than whether you did it, 'cause I know you did, is why you did it. If you tell me that, I'll give you a piece of good advice."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not even your advice is free, huh, Emmett?" she asked. And, "You tight sonofabitch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt shook a finger at her, but before he could speak, she said, "That Tripp kid found out that Jake was one of the boys who was there when Kelly died. He told Jim that Jake came in with his shirt off, and he saw that Liberty head above his belt buckle, and that Kelly had told him that she was fuckin' some rough guy they called Liberty because of the tattoo. He was going to spill the beans to some newspaper guy. So Jim killed him. But by the time he got home, he was scared to death. He knew all about this crime-scene stuff, and he thought they'd figure it out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Emmett's face had gone still, and he said, "So… he did right by us. Why'd you kill him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He said if they got him, he wasn't going to prison. He said he knew what happened to cops in prison. He got a little drunk, and he started to cry, and that's what he said. What he meant was, he'd make a deal. He started out right, but then… he would of took us down."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A deal."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's right. I mean, Emmett, I know you've got your theories and all, but the state's got its theories, and if they knew about your little religion, they'd put you under the jail. All of you. All of us. And I think there'd be some who'd talk. Look to Alma: I hear she's got the Bible real bad."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The Bible is the core…" Einstadt said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "This is Kate Spooner you're talking to," Spooner said. "You've been talking Bible to me since I was five years old, and your dad before you, and his dad before him, and all you ever hear is Lot and his daughters and Tamar and Judah and Jacob and Leah and Rachel and you don't hear about anything else. I'll tell you what, Emmet, reading the Bible for the fuckin' parts is not really reading the Bible. That's okay with me; but now Alma is reading the other parts."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll take care of Alma," Rooney said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Rooney, excuse me, but you couldn't take care of a fuckin' rock," Spooner said. They heard the sound of a car in the parking lot, and Einstadt stepped to the window and looked out. Pizza delivery truck.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You got a pizza coming?" he asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No," she said, and she took the moment to step up beside him and away from the two other men, to look out the window, and then step quickly past them so she could sit on the far end of the couch. That was a comfort, because her.45 fell under her hand, nestled in the pocket off the end of the couch.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She asked, "So what advice have you got, Emmett?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt stared at her, his mouth turned down in a sour line, and he said, "They know a woman did it. They're probably going to get some of this DNA stuff off Jim's body-that's the word in town. They say you were sucking his cock, and they can get the DNA from dried spit. So if it was you, you best stay away from the cops. And after you've kept your head down for a while, you might think of moving someplace else. Like Alaska, or somewhere."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "I'll think about that, Emmett. Now, I've got to eat my lunch, or I'll be no good the rest of the day. So you go along. And you remember, I put my ass on the line for all of us."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Bullshit. You done it because you wanted to. If it had to be done, there'd be better ways to do it," Einstadt said. "Coulda had him out to the house, taken him out back, and buried the body in the field. Never would have found it in a thousand years."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's water down the drain," she said. "I had to do something, and I did it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Morgan took a step toward her, but spoke to the others: "We oughta get her airtight one more time, then wring her neck."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She lifted her hand from over the arm of the couch, with the.45 in her grip, and laid the hand and gun across her lap. "Time to leave," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A quick relay of glances, and Rooney took a step back. She was crazier than a bucket of frogs. WHEN THEY'D GONE, Spooner put the.45 back in the couch sleeve, looked out to the parking lot, saw them talking and looking up at her apartment window. Cold out: steam coming out of their mouths as they talked, mostly Morgan and Einstadt. Rooney's opinions were given to him by Einstadt, especially since he'd given Rooney Alma and the girls.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Maybe, Spooner thought, she ought to give a gun to Alma. Or the girls. Surprise that old sonofabitch someday. She waited until the men got in their trucks and rolled out of the parking lot, then went and put a Lean Cuisine chicken carbonara in the microwave. While she waited for it to ding, she thought about Morgan and his threat, went and got the small 9mm Taurus pistol from her purse, and put it in the pocket of her fleece.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The microwave dinged, and she took out the plastic tray, ate standing up at the kitchen counter, thought about DNA, thought she should know more about it, and had just tossed the tray into the trash when the doorbell rang.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The doorbell hadn't rung unexpectedly more than three or four times since she'd been in the apartment. She went to the door and looked through the peephole, and saw a tall, blond man, hatless, waiting in the hall. Didn't know him. Wary, she left the chain on the door, opened it, and peeked out.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Miz Spooner? I'm Virgil Flowers, with the state Bureau of Criminal Apprehension. I'm investigating the death of your ex-husband, and some related problems. I'd like to talk to you a minute."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh…" A chill ran up her spine. They were already here. "I've got to get back to work," she said. "I'm due back in ten minutes."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I could talk to your boss. I'm sure he'd be cooperative…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She looked at him for another two seconds, then said, "Let me get the chain." She took the chain off, opened the door, and said, "Come in. I really haven't seen Jim in a long time. I heard about it, him being killed, but I just… I mean, I felt a little sad, I guess, we were married for five years, but that's all back then."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And Virgil thought, Interesting. She's lying already.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil stepped inside, looked around. Compact kitchen off to the left, with the smell of pasta still in the air; a small living room straight ahead, down a hall, with another door to the left, presumably to a bedroom. Neat, not expensive. "Okay, well, if we could sit down for five minutes…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They sat in the living room, Virgil taking the couch as it faced the television, and started with a thirty-second summary of what he thought: that Tripp had killed Flood for reasons unknown, that Crocker had killed Tripp to hide something that Tripp had known-something linked to the killing-and that both killings were somehow linked to the murder of Kelly Baker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know if Jim knew any of those people? The Floods, the Bakers, the Tripp family… any of those?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He and Jake Flood were old friends since they were kids," she said. "We all came from the same place. And we knew the Bakers, 'cause we were all from the same part of the county, and the same business. Went to church services together."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're from the same area? Over around Battenberg?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, yeah-my folks have a farm a mile down the road from the Floods. They all go back like to the nineteen hundreds, the families. Came from Germany. So we all know each other." As she was talking, she was trying in her mind to stay out front of the conversation: what he could find out easily, she'd tell him, so she couldn't be caught in a lie.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When Iowa investigated, I guess they talked to all the folks in the church to see if anybody knew or heard anything?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She shook her head: "I don't think the church ever came into it. It's not really a church, you know. There's no church. We'd have services at different people's houses, usually in the barn, unless it's too cold. Sometimes, there'll be a couple different services going on, so we don't all go to the same one. We talk about the Bible, and all of that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. Okay." Virgil scratched his head. "I thought Iowa had been all over everything-that they'd have talked to all of the Bakers' friends and neighbors. Anyway, when Kelly Baker was killed, did you have any feeling of what she might have been involved in? Who she might have been hanging with? Was she still going to the religious services, or had she dropped away?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I really couldn't tell you. I mean, she was there, but the Bakers are down at the far south end of the county, so we didn't see them every day," Spooner said. "I really don't know. I mean, I guess… they say, the word is, she was sexually active. I was surprised, but I wasn't really close enough to her to have any… instinct… about that. Maybe she was working in town, maybe she got loose somehow. I don't know."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Were you homeschooled?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, yes," she said. "Reading, writing, arithmetic, German. Every year, for thirteen years, five days a week."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is that part of the, uh, religion?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's one of the main parts-to keep the kids away from the influences in schools," she said. She glanced at her watch. "I've really got to go."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked, "Jim-was he violent with you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She shook her head: "No. Jim was boring. That's why I left. He'd get up, eat eggs, go to work, come home, eat dinner, sit on the couch and drink beer, go to bed. Every day. I couldn't see living my whole life like that. This idea that he could have killed the Tripp boy… I mean, that's very strange. I couldn't believe it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know if he was dating anyone?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know. Really. I haven't seen him in years… All I know is history." She looked at her watch again and said, "Now I've got two minutes to walk two blocks."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Come on," Virgil said, "I'll give you a ride. Where do you work?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "At the CVS. I'm the assistant manager, I take care of the non-pharmacy items."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On the way down the hall, zipping their parkas, he said, "I'm interested in the relationship between Jacob Flood and the Bakers. Flood and Baker both being murdered. Were they close?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Everybody in the church is fairly close-that's mostly eighty or a hundred families, I guess. But I don't know that the Floods were any closer to the Bakers than anybody else-they're at the other end of the county from each other."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "I chatted with Emmett Einstadt about Jacob Flood, and their relationships with the Bakers, Kelly Baker. He seemed to have about the same feeling as you did-close, but not every day. He was pretty upset about Kelly, you know, in a German way. If you know what I mean… My mother is pure German."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She smiled. "I do know," she said. "Emmett never shows much, but because there aren't so many church members, compared to the big churches, when somebody dies, you feel it. He gave a nice talk at her funeral."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded and said, "That's good. That's good." They were outside, and he pointed her at the truck, and they climbed inside.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How long has the church been around? Is this a longtime thing, or did you all get converted?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Been around since the families came over from the Old Country," Spooner said. "My great-grandfather was in it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Most people marry into the church?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, yeah. Because we know each other all our lives, and we have all these background things-don't go to regular schools, so we don't have any regular school friends. I always thought I might marry an outsider, if I fell in love, but when it came time to get married, I wound up with Jim. Somebody I'd known all my life."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They pulled into the pharmacy, and Virgil said, "I might come back and talk to you again. I'm puzzled about Jim's part in all of this. Why he might kill somebody like Tripp, and why he'd be so quickly killed in return."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't have the faintest idea," she said. "But if the Tripp boy knew both Kelly and Jacob, and you know he killed one of them…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But then why did Jim kill him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's the mystery," she said. "The only thing I can think of, is that he went a little crazy if the boy told him about killing Jake. Maybe he made a joke out of it, or something. Jim and Jake grew up together-they used to hunt and trap together, when they were kids, wander around the countryside. That's all I can think of."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But then who'd kill Jim? And why?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She shrugged. "Don't know. Have you investigated the Tripps?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, we think the killer was a woman."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh. Well, it wasn't me," she said. "Mrs. Tripp is a woman…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're right. You're right. I'll think about that," Virgil said. He put out his hand and they shook, and she popped the door and climbed out, wiggled her fingers at him as she went through the door.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil sat staring at the door for a minute, running it all through his head.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt had lied about not knowing the Bakers; he knew them quite well. That seemed critical, somehow. With Crocker being close to Flood, and married to Spooner, the church seemed more and more central to the whole situation. The only person not involved with it was Bobby Tripp.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And he wondered who'd been in Spooner's apartment, not very long before himself, who'd left behind the damp footprints on the carpet, big bootlike footprints. And whether those footprints had anything to do with the fact that the hausfrau-looking Kathleen Spooner had a pistol in her pocket.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And he wondered about the color of the lipstick found on Crocker's penis. Most Minnesota working women didn't use lipstick, during the day, anyway. It was like a Minnesota thing. But Spooner wore it. Could the crime-scene people get enough of it off Crocker to match it to lipstick in Spooner's bathroom or dressing table?\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Stuff to think about: and while he was thinking about it, he carefully peeled off his parka and pulled back the sleeve of his shirt. He had a two-inch piece of double-sided carpet tape on his wrist. The sticky side was covered with fuzz, with a few dark hairs, from Kathleen Spooner's couch.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Should be enough for DNA, he thought, if the lab guys would just give him the time. He peeled the tape off his wrist and stuck it in a Ziploc bag. Might not be an entirely legal search, but he was invited in… and once he knew, he could always come back.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Or not.\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 9\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil headed south to Iowa, and called Bell Wood, the agent with the Iowa Division of Criminal Investigation: "I'm going down to Estherville," he said, when Wood came up. "There're interesting things going on, and I need to talk to John Baker and his family."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You won't get much. They were pretty much mystified-Kelly backed out of their driveway and went on down the road," Wood said. "We took a look at them, and nothing came up. We interviewed them all separately-John and… I can't remember the wife's name…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Luanne."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. John and Luanne, and their kids, and they all had the same story. Not rehearsed, just… the same."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. But I want to ask them about these new killings, see if they knew any of the people involved… Did you guys look into their religion?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not really. I remember they were churchy. Very dark dressers, kids homeschooled, and all that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. Okay-listen, would it be possible to get a highway patrol guy, or maybe an Estherville cop, whichever is better, to ride along with me? Somebody with an Iowa badge?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let me make a call," Wood said. "I'll get back to you before you're there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thanks."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil… you're getting somewhere?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Somewhere. But it's murky. I'll stay in touch." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The highway patrolman's name was Bill Clinton, "but not that Bill Clinton," he said, as he shook Virgil's hand. He was a thick-set, shaved-head man of perhaps thirty-five; he had three fleshy wrinkles that rolled down the back of his neck like stair steps. They'd hooked up at a cafe across the street from the Emmet County Courthouse.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hope you're a Democrat, anyway," Virgil said. Virgil got a cup of coffee while Clinton finished his lunch.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Clinton shook his head. "Lifelong Republican. My old man is the Republican county chairman down in Sac County. But I didn't mind-it was kinda fun. I was in the army back then."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil gave him a quick outline of the investigation, and Clinton whistled and said, "Man, that's a hell of thing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You heard anything about Kelly Baker since last year?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, sure, all kinds of stuff. But it's all bullshit," Clinton said. "There was a cop from Des Moines who came up here on his own and was poking around, looking for Satanists. One of the churches here, pretty fundamental, he got the pastor all churned up, but it didn't come to anything. Nobody believed it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Neither do I," Virgil said. "I've met a couple Satanists. They're about what you expect-people who never got over Halloween."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Clinton nodded. "Exactly right. People here are pretty commonsensical. The thing nobody could get around was what actually happened to her. The state ran the investigation, but technically, the Emmet County sheriff was in charge, so they got all the reports. When the autopsy came in, word about it got out in a couple of hours. Whips and multiple partners. People here look at the Internet, just like anybody, but they don't believe that stuff happens here. Not with little farm girls." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil had called ahead to the Bakers' and had gotten directions on how to get there. Clinton left his patrol car in Estherville, and they rode together out to the Baker place. The Bakers' house was a low, pale yellow rambler, with a miniature windmill in the front yard and an attached garage. The usual collection of farm sheds and buildings stood behind it, along with an early-twentieth-century brick silo, with no roof. A collection of rusted farm machinery was parked behind the old silo.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 As they went up the drive, Virgil asked, "You know anything about these folks?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not a thing. I looked them up after Bell Wood called, and law enforcement doesn't even know they exist. Not even a traffic ticket." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 John Baker was Kelly Baker's uncle. He was a tall, thin man with hollowed cheeks, long, lank black hair and a beard going gray; he wore oversized steel-framed glasses, like aviators, dark trousers, and a dark wool shirt. His wife was more of the same, without the beard, and with smaller glasses, and an ankle-length skirt that looked homemade.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A brilliant crazy quilt, made of postage-stamp-sized snips of cloth, hung from pegs on the front-room wall; Virgil liked quilts, and this was a good one. He took a minute to look at it, as they were sitting down, and realized that in its natural craziness, it concealed a spring landscape.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The house smelled of vegetable soup-very good vegetable soup-and something else, some kind of herb, perhaps.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Terrific quilt," he said to Luanne Baker.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She nodded, and then, almost reluctantly, "My mom made it." She had a dry, tinny voice, and Virgil realized that she was frightened.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil smiled and asked, "Do you quilt yourself?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes, I do," she said, and nothing more.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 John Baker asked, "Is this about Kelly? It must be."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Yes, it is…" He looked around, tipping his head, and asked, "I understand you have kids?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They're over at a neighbor's," John Baker said. "We got them out of the way of this-they're scared enough."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right," Virgil said. "What we've got going up north… you may have heard some of it-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You have a killer running around loose," John Baker said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. And we think the killer knows something about what happened to Kelly. We're linking up the cases. For one thing, Kelly, and two other victims, Jim Crocker and Jacob Flood, are members of your church. That doesn't necessarily mean anything-there are a lot of church members out in the same area-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A lot of people don't like us. They say we're standoffish," Luanne Baker blurted. "Kelly was wearing her bonnet when she left, and I think some perverts spotted her and they took her right off the street. This boy who killed Jacob, he must've been one of them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil shook his head. "That really doesn't fit with the facts, Mrs. Baker. It appears that Kelly had been with these men more than once."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't believe it," she said. "She was a good, cheerful girl. I would have spotted something like that. We all would have. There's something rotten in the state of Iowa, and I think that medical examiner is part of it. You know, he's a Muslim?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't see-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then you should look harder," John Baker said. "A good Christian girl gets kidnapped off the city streets and who examines the body? A Muslim. And what happens? People start saying stuff about our church. Start tearing it down." THEY ALL SAT looking at one another for a moment, the Bakers rigid in their chairs, Bill Clinton staring at them with his mouth open, not quite in amusement, and Virgil finally said, "Why don't we just talk about what happened that day? When Kelly was here. Did she leave in a rush? Was she in a hurry? Did she seem like she had an appointment?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 John Baker: "No. You know why she came down?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She was going down to the locker in Estherville. My brother and I go in together on a couple of stocker calves every spring; we got a piece of pasture down by the crick. We take 'em to the locker in the fall, and she drove down to pick up some beef. She stopped here on the way."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There was no beef in her car when it was found," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. She never got there. There were two women and a man working at the locker place, and they said they never saw her. The police believed them, and so do I. I know them, a bit, and they're okay, in my opinion."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "So she left here, in daylight, and went to Estherville, and something happened there. She met somebody or was picked up, probably in daylight, if she was on her way to the locker-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's not the way I see it," Baker said. "I think somebody probably stopped her on the road, flagged her down, asking for directions or something, or acted like they was having car problems, and they took her. And the accomplice drove the car to Estherville. There's parking right at the locker, and the car was found four or five blocks from there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe she decided to stop and do some shopping-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's not the way I see it," Baker said. "For one thing, it was later in the afternoon by that time, and she was picking up beef for dinner. Len likes his dinner at five o'clock sharp, so she would have gone straight to the locker, and then home."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But you said she wasn't in a hurry when she left," Bill Clinton said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She wasn't. She had time, but she had to move along."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe she was in a little bit of a hurry," Luanne Baker said. "But she wasn't in a rush or anything."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let me ask you about the church," Virgil began.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 John Baker interrupted: "What religion are you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil evaded a direct answer: "My father's a Lutheran minister. Over in Marshall." He paused, then asked, "Is it possible that Kelly was meeting, or was flagged down by, members of the church? Why would she stop for strangers, or go with strangers?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Because we do that around here," John Baker said. "If somebody has a problem, we don't expect them to be crazy killers. We stop and help out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's nice," Bill Clinton said. He fished a piece of Dentyne gum from his shirt pocket, unwrapped it with one hand, and popped it in his mouth. "But I thought you were standoffish."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's what people say, but we help as much as anybody," John Baker said. "We're just private in our beliefs. This whole country is dying from a lack of good morals and proper behavior, and we don't want no part of it. We keep ourselves out of it, and we keep our children out of it, and we tend our farms."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You don't know any church members who might have run off the tracks, or had a reputation for being a little wild…?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's not the church," John Baker said. "It's not. You're barking up the wrong tree. You know who killed Jake Flood. That boy is the one who did it-he's the devil. He's the devil in this. I heard that you think Jim Crocker killed him, and maybe he did, but if he did, it was because that boy attacked him. I think Jake found out something, and the boy killed him, and then maybe Jim asked him something, and he went after Jim-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then Jim was murdered-" Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "By the accomplices," John Baker said. "It's as plain as the nose on your face."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil pushed them on the church, but got nowhere. A bit of history: the church members had been a branch of a fundamentalist movement in Germany that began in the 1830s, and had immigrated en masse to the U.S. in the 1880s. After arriving here, the group split up. Most of the various branches had eventually merged with other churches and movements around the Midwest and, finally, except for the Minnesota branch, had disappeared.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're the last of them," John Baker said. "The last who know the old ways."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked for a while longer, but got no useful information-Kelly Baker had arrived, had sat in the kitchen and chatted, had looked at a Christian computer game with the children, and had left, moving quickly but not rushed, to go to the locker. That was all. Back in the car, they rolled out the driveway, and Virgil asked Bill Clinton, "What do you think?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not much," he said. "That thing about the Muslim medical examiner…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You see that a bit out here. People have ideas about Muslims and Jews," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, but… not like that. Not like some giant conspiracy," Clinton said. "Then there was that whole thing about morals and good behavior. I'm not sure exactly… I'd like to know what their definition of 'moral' is. I mean, you smell that place?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You mean the soup? It smelled pretty good."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I mean the smoke. The dope. The spliff, the ganj. As these good Germans would say, the dank."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil put a hand to his forehead and rubbed. "That's what it was. I was thinking it was some kind of herb in the soup."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It is some kind of herb, but I don't think it was in the soup," Clinton said. "I think it was in the curtains and the couch and the rugs. I think she was cooking up that soup to cover the odor. Those people are Christian fundamentalist stoners. I was sitting there grinning the whole time, listening to them. They were totally full of shit… depending on how you define 'moral.'"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What is it with these guys?" Virgil asked. "These church people… I talked to one today who was carrying a gun in her pocket. I think some of them know a lot more about Kelly Baker than they're saying. I think-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll tell you what it is," Bill Clinton said. "What it is, is, something is seriously fucked. I wish you luck in detecting what it is."\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 10\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil called Coakley, who suggested that they meet at the Holiday Inn restaurant, away from the office and "not at the cafe, where half the town is, waiting for you to show up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Works for me," Virgil said. "I'll see you in twenty." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Most sheriffs in Minnesota wore uniforms; a few didn't. Virgil hadn't seen Coakley in a uniform until she showed up at the Holiday Inn. When she took her parka off, she was wearing a star and had a pistol on her hip.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil had gotten to the restaurant a couple of minutes earlier, and already had a booth. When she came up, he said, "You look like a cop."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Feels weird, wearing a uniform," she said. "I wore one for five years before I became an investigator, and never did like it. But since I was working with the girls today…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Show some solidarity," Virgil said. "They come up with anything?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nothing that we didn't know. Crocker and Jacob Flood were close. They all belong to a fundamentalist church that goes back to the Old Country, meaning Germany. They homeschool their kids, church services move around from one home to another."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Services are held in barns," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nobody seems to know much about the religion, except that it's conservative," Coakley said. "They're all farmers, or come from farm families. Some people say they're standoffish, but other people say they know members of the church who work in town and are like anyone else. Which sounds like Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A waiter came up, and they ordered hamburgers and fries, and Coakley got coffee and Virgil got a Diet Coke, and when the waiter went away, Coakley asked, "Did Spooner have anything to contribute?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not much," Virgil said. "She kept trying to get around the questions. But I expect she's the one who killed Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley's eyebrows went up. "What?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She let me sit on her couch, and using a special BCA investigatory technique, I got some of her hair," he said. "I need to get it up to our lab. Then I'm going to use unfair tactics to get the lab to do some rush processing on it, so we ought to know for sure by day after tomorrow."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil, how…?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil told her about it: about the gun in Spooner's pocket, about the lipstick, how nobody knew of anyone Crocker was seeing. "On that basis alone-somebody familiar enough with him to get involved with oral sex-she'd be a suspect. The gun thing is big. She's a member of the church, born to it. I've got a feeling that the church could be involved here. Or maybe there's just something going on with this tight little knot of people, coming down through the generations. Most of them are related to each other, if I understood Spooner right. Lot of intermarriage."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If she's the one, that'd be a pretty amazing clearance," Coakley said. "It's like you plucked her out of the air."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nah. All you do is, you look around," Virgil said. "Everybody says Crocker didn't have much to do with women, and the woman we know that he had something to do with, happens to carry a gun in her pocket. So she knows how to use one, and is maybe prepared to do it. Plus, she wears lipstick, which most women out here don't, except on special occasions. It's just… obvious."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if she killed him for some personal reason that has nothing to do with Flood or Tripp?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil was already shaking his head. "Too big a coincidence. I'll tell you something else. I led Spooner on a bit…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How unlike you…" But she said it with a smile.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "… and she told me that Einstadt gave a nice talk at Kelly Baker's funeral. Einstadt and the Floods and the Bakers know each other very well, and they're lying about it. Why would they do that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They're covering something up. Maybe Kelly Baker's death," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She looked at him for a long time, then said, "Maybe. But it's a jump."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The food came, and Virgil asked if she could send one of her deputies up to the BCA, in St. Paul, with Spooner's hair samples. She nodded. "Most of them would be happy for the chance, on the county's dime. Do some shopping."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll give you the sample when we leave," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She was picking at her food without much interest, and then she said, "I was talking to a friend up at the BCA. She said you've been married so often that the judge gives you a discount."\par
