\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So how many times, then?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Three," Virgil admitted. "But it's not as bad as it sounds."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tell me the truth," Coakley said. "How bad did it hurt? When you got divorced?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It hurt," Virgil said. "I'm human."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But she said all of this, all three marriages and divorces, were like in five years. And you have another girlfriend about every fifteen minutes. And that you've supposedly slept with witnesses. I don't know. I was kind of shocked."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hey…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Because when I got divorced, I mean, I was lying there for months, at night, trying to figure out what went wrong-and whose fault it was. I still do it," she said. "You know. I could no more have gotten married again in six months… I was still a basket case in six months."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I didn't have so much of that," Virgil said. "It was pretty clear, pretty quick, that me and my wives weren't going to make it. One of them, it was about a week and a half, you know, that we had the talk."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's absurd," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah," Virgil said. "I know. I did like the first one. But she had lots of plans. I didn't have much input into them, and I wasn't doing what she planned. Then, one day, I just wasn't in the plans anymore. She'd decided to outsource her expectations."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How about sex. Did she outsource the sex?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not that I know of-that wasn't the problem," Virgil said. "The problem was more… business-related. She'd decided I couldn't really be monetized."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hmph," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That was a denigrating hmph."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well. Might as well get it out there," she said. She glanced around the room. "The thing is, when Larry stopped having sex with me, I thought maybe he was… just losing interest in sex. I'd never gotten that much out of it. I'm not especially orgasmic, and so, I just let it go. But then, he dumps me off, for this other… person… with big… and I start to wonder, maybe I'm just a complete screwup as a woman."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil held up his hands, didn't want to hear it. "Whoa, whoa, this is a lot of information-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "Shut up, Virgil-I'm talking. Anyway, I'm wondering, am I a complete screwup? The major relationship in my life is a disaster-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hey, you've got three kids," Virgil said. "Is that a disaster?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Shut up. Anyway, I know I'm not all that attractive-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're very attractive," Virgil said. "Jesus, Lee, get your head out of your ass."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, see, nobody ever told me that-and you might be lying," she said. "I suspect somebody who got married and divorced three times in five years probably lies a lot."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So, you can see where this is going," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Of course you can. I'm the sheriff of Warren County. There are twenty-two thousand people here, and all twenty-two thousand know who I am. I can't go flitting around, finding out about myself. If I pick out a man, that's pretty much it. But how can I pick out a man if maybe I'm a total screwup as a woman? I mean, maybe I should be gay. I kind of dress like a guy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you feel gay?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, I don't. What I feel like, Virgil, is a little experimentation, something quick and shallow, somebody with experience," she said. "I can't experiment with the locals, without a lot of talk. So I need to pick somebody out and get the job done."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She peered at him with the blue eye and the green eye, waiting, and Virgil said, finally, "Well, you've got my attention." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When Virgil left the Holiday Inn, he drove over to the cafe, thinking about Coakley on the way-the proposition seemed pretty bald-parked, went inside, and ordered a piece of cherry pie and a Diet Coke. Jacoby, the owner, sidled over with the pie and asked, "Hey, Virg. Any more news?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The close-by people stopped eating, and one man who'd been at the end of the bar picked up his coffee and moved to a closer stool.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked, "Have you ever heard of a man, or a place, called Liberty? Some man around here, or some place around here?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Liberty?" Jacoby moved his lips as though he were sampling the word. Then, "No, I never did. Is it important?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Could help us out with the Kelly Baker murder," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There's a 'New Liberty,' but it's way down in Iowa, way down past Cedar Rapids," said a guy in the booth behind Virgil. "That wouldn't be it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I got a feeling it's something around here," Virgil said. "And maybe a person. Huh. I guess I'll just have to keep asking around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, if we hear anything, we'll let you know," Jacoby said. He watched as Virgil took a bite of the pie. "How is it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I've had worse," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He just can't remember when," said the guy on the stool. HAVING DONE his data dump at the cafe, Virgil was headed out to his truck, followed by one of the customers, a thin man with thin hair, wearing a sheepskin-lined jean jacket and leather gloves: a cowboy-looking guy, except for his big round plastic-rimmed glasses, and not ungrizzled.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He said, "Uh, Virgil. I need to chat for a minute. About the Tripp boy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure," Virgil said. "Back in the cafe, here, somewhere? Or we could take a ride in my truck."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not here. How about the truck?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The man's name was Dick Street, he said, and he had a farm out toward Battenberg, though he lived in Homestead. "I use the elevator at Battenberg, and met the Tripp kid. You know he was a football player?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. Hurt himself this year, was going out to Marshall next year," Virgil said, as he backed out of the parking place and started around the block.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yup. Anyway, I mentioned to my daughter that he seemed to be a pretty nice kid. Hard worker, good-looking. She was the same grade as him. She said, 'Yes, but I think he's gay.'"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Your daughter said that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. I almost fell off my chair," Street said. "I said, 'Why do you think that?' and she said, 'I don't know, I just think so.' Turns out, some of her girlfriends thought the same thing, that he might be a homosexual."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did everybody think that? His schoolmates?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know. But it wasn't exactly nobody. Some people suspected. So anyway, if he was a homosexual, I guess that's neither here nor there, when it comes to killing somebody. But. This sort of came to be a hot topic around the dinner table, because my daughter also thought that he might've been… doing something… with somebody."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Does she have any idea who?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was gonna say, you oughta talk to her," Street said. "She works at the Christmas Barn. Anyway, I can tell you that a lot of the farmers around here don't care too much for homosexuals. I was thinking, maybe Flood found out and said something, like he was going to tell everybody. And Bob Tripp hit him to stop that from happening. I mean, if he's gay, maybe he'd lose his football scholarship or something?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I hadn't thought of that," Virgil said, though he had.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Or, maybe he had something going with Jake Flood, and it was like a lovers' thing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Jake Flood was married," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. But just between you, me, and the fence post, there was something not quite right about him," Street said. "He had a strange way of looking at people. There was a sex thing in it. You know how some guys will look a woman up and down, seeing what she got? You got the feeling that Jake did that with everybody. Men, women. Whatever. Well, not dogs or anything. Maybe a heifer, if it was a good-looking one." He shot a quick glance at Virgil, and hastily added, "That was a joke, Virgil."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm laughing myself sick, inside," Virgil said, but he said it with a grin. "Back to Jake Flood…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He was a weird one. I would not have wanted one of my daughters to be around him," Street said. "I just wonder if that weirdness might have set something off with Bobby?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. Something to think about." They were almost back at the cafe. "I'll stop and talk to your daughter. What's her name?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maicy. She'll talk to you. She's a talkative girl."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They turned the corner and Street said, "You can let me out by that Tundra up there, the gray one. Don't tell anybody what I said about this-the fact is, we don't know if Bobby was a homosexual, and it's not right to bad-mouth the dead. But since more people were getting killed, I thought I should mention this."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Glad you did, Dick. Thank you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The Christmas Barn is four blocks straight ahead, on your right. They also sell some of the best saltwater taffy on the face of the earth."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. How do you like that Tundra?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's all right. It's my first Jap truck," Street said. "They had a recall for the floor mats, and then for the gas pedal, but I haven't had any trouble. Probably go back to Chevy, though. I don't know why I ever jumped the fence. You have any trouble with your 4Runner?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not yet," Virgil said. "I asked you about the Tundra because the 4Runner is based on it…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They chatted about trucks for a few minutes, especially the tow package, then Street looked at his watch and said, "Got to get back. See you at the cafe, maybe."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thanks again," Virgil said, and he rolled on down the avenue. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Maicy was a talkative girl: "A lot of us thought Bobby might be a little, you know, gay. We'd be sitting around talking, and he wouldn't be checking you out," she said. "He'd be checking out the guys. Not real obviously, he wasn't drooling over them or anything, but you could kind of feel it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil: "You don't know if he was actually actively involved with somebody?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know, but I could tell you who might. He had a friend named Jay Wenner. Jay's kind of a geek-totally straight, though. He's up at the university in Minneapolis, at the Institute of Technology. You should call him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll do that," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called the BCA researcher, Sandy, from the car, and asked her to find Wenner's phone number. She said, "Hold on." A minute later, she was back with a cell phone number.\par
