\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How'd you get this phone number?" Wenner asked. "It's unlisted."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A BCA researcher looked it up on a computer," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You have to excuse me, but that doesn't sound likely," Wenner said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Look. I'm sitting here in my truck in Homestead, and I could go over to your parents' house, and show them my ID, and have them call you. Or, you could call the BCA and ask for the duty officer, and get my phone number. But, one way or the other, I need to talk to you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. You make the offer, you're probably okay. I've been reading about Bobby on the net. I'm like totally freaked. So: what do you want to know?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think Bobby was gay?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A moment of silence, then, "Who are you going to tell about this?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nobody who doesn't need to know," Virgil said. "The question is, did some kind of homosexual involvement lead to his murder? Or his murder of Jacob Flood?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh. I couldn't tell you about that. But he was gay," Wenner said. "Only a couple of us knew. He'd had some contact with… somebody. I don't know who that was."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You mean sexual contact? We haven't heard that, though we know he was talking to a gay man in a more… what would you call it? More of a mentoring thing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Pat Sullivan. Not him, I think there was somebody else," Wenner said. "Do you know about that Kelly Baker girl, who got killed a year or so ago?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes, and we know that she and Bobby had some kind of relationship."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They did. I think she might have known somebody else who was gay, and put Bob in touch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Was Baker a hooker?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Interesting question," Wenner said. "I have no idea. I only saw her a few times, and she looked like a regular girl except… she looked kind of beat up, too. You know?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not exactly," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, sometimes you see girls who look like they've been around a little too much," Wenner said. "They start to look tired when they're still young. She looked like that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good description… I know what you mean. Did her relationship with Bobby extend to sex?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No-but they talked about sex all the time," Wenner said. "Bob once told me that she told him about doing some really freaky things, but he thought maybe she was lying, because he couldn't believe she'd do that stuff. But then, a friend of ours from Northwest said the Iowa cops came around and were asking about whether she might have been a prostitute. Or something like that-that was the idea."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But she didn't go to Northwest."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, but she knew kids who did. So they were checking out the guys."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Wenner didn't have much more-said he'd be back to Homestead for the funeral, that he'd be a pallbearer. "I knew that guy since first grade. I didn't care if he was gay, he was a good guy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You didn't see the violence in him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I didn't, except on the football field," Wenner said. "The Flood thing is hard to believe. Maybe he was framed, or something. You think?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not really," Virgil said. "It's pretty clear he killed Flood. Listen, if you think of anything else, call me. You can get me through the BCA, or I may see you at the funeral."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "One more thing," Wenner said. "Pat Sullivan and Bob were talking quite a bit, and we were all talking at the Dairy Queen a few times, and Kelly was there. If Sullivan ever saw who Kelly was hanging with, another guy… that might be the one. If she was really involved in some heavy sex things, maybe she gathered up gay guys to be her friends. You know, people she could trust."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good thought, Jay. Thank you."\\\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called Pat Sullivan. He was told the reporter was in Mankato for a regional flood-preparation meeting and wouldn't be back until late. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil met Coakley back at her office, where she'd been talking with a couple of deputies. She looked up when he stuck his head in, and she said, "You got something."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe. I need all that paper from Iowa, again, and a place to read it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She looked at him for a long moment, considering him, and not in a collegial way, Virgil thought, and then she nodded.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And Virgil thought: If what Wenner said was true, and Baker had set Tripp up with a homosexual contact, then there was at least one person out there who might know as much as Baker did-and exactly what kind of activities Baker had been into. But tracking that person down would be a problem, especially if he had to do it without broadcasting the fact that Tripp had been gay.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He would do that-broadcast, sit in the cafe and tell the patrons about it-if it became necessary, but he hoped it wouldn't.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley got him the Iowa paper, a spot in an interview room, and a Diet Coke, and he started wading through the paper again, looking for anything that might pinpoint a possible lover.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Two hours: he found nothing.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley was staring at a computer, and he asked, "Are you online?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. What's up?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Could we go out to Google Earth and spot the Baker place?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We can." She hit a few keys, enlarged the screen a couple of times, found the house, lost it, found it again, and enlarged to the maximum. "What do you need?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I want to know who lives in the houses closest to them." Virgil got her to change the scale up and down, to get a map of a couple dozen farmhouses within a couple miles of the Baker place. "Print that," he said. And, "I wonder who runs the rural route out there?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We can find that out," Coakley said, looking at her watch. "Should still be some carriers around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She got on the phone, called the post office, talked to somebody, hung up, and said, "Clare Kreuger's your girl. She's not there at the moment, but she's due back in anytime."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good-now, where's the post office?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Are you going back out there? To the Bakers'?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. Gonna whisper in the ears of the neighbors… after I talk to Clare.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 " Kreuger was skeptical: "What you're saying is, you want to turn their friends against them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, no. I don't want friends. I want people who already don't like them," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That just seems rotten," the carrier said. She was a dusty-looking woman, who looked like she'd spent too much time in the wind. She wore a nylon parka, nylon wind pants, and galoshes. They were standing at the post office loading dock, where Clare had parked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It is a little rotten," Virgil said. "But we have four dead people, and a killer still on the loose. I wouldn't do it otherwise."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Kreuger said, "Neither would I. But you got me. Too many dead people. I know there's bad blood between the Bakers and Brian Craig, because of a drainage problem off the Bakers' land that they've never been able to work out. There's another guy, Peter Van Mann, and I don't think they get along, either. I don't know what the problem is, something about a dog. That's before my time on the route. Let's go inside, and I'll spot them on the map…" \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The sun was sliding hard to the southwest when Virgil pulled into the Craig place. Craig, said his wife, was out in the barn trying to fix the front frame of a hay wagon, which had bent while they were pulling in the last cut of hay in late summer. They had lived with it then, but once winter shut down the field work, it was time to do repairs.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil found Craig struggling to get the left side of the frame up on a jack, under a couple of work lights. He saw Virgil come through the door, stopped struggling, and asked, "Who are you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A cop. State Bureau of Criminal Apprehension," Virgil said. "I need to talk to you for a bit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "About what?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "About Kelly Baker, and the Bakers in general," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know much about Kelly…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 His wife pushed through the door behind them. She'd pulled on a letter jacket and run over to listen in.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll tell you the truth," Virgil said. "We've got a hell of a problem here and…" He hesitated, then asked, "What's the deal with your frame?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I cut out the bent part, and when I jack up one side, there's enough torque to twist the frame when I'm jacking up the other."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let me give you a hand with that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Craig didn't say no, and they spent five minutes getting both sides of the front frame up on jacks and lined up to each other. Craig fit a piece of steel across the gap and clamped it in place, put on welding glasses, and said, "Don't look at the spot." He made a number of quick welds to hold it square, and the barn was suffused with the odor of burning iron. When it cooled, he used a spare piece of L-bar to check the squareness, and took the clamps off.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thanks," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You want to come in for coffee?" his wife asked. "It's pretty cold out here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil shrugged, and Craig said, "Might as well. I can do the final weld anytime, now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They sat at the kitchen table, and Virgil said, "I understand that you and the Bakers haven't always gotten along. One thing cops do is, we talk to people who don't like other people, because they're usually less reluctant to talk. It sounds mean, but that's the way it is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Does sound mean," Craig's wife said, and Virgil said, "You didn't mention your first name."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Judy," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It is mean," Virgil said. "But we're talking some nasty murders here. I've spoken to the Bakers, and what they tell me isn't as consistent with the evidence as it should be."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "For example?" Craig asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "For example, Jacob Flood and members of the Flood family say they don't know the Bakers that well, and the Bakers agree with that, but we've talked to other people who have suggested that they're actually quite close. And that they're all involved in a fundamentalist religion that's really pretty tight."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Craig and his wife glanced at each other, and then Judy Craig asked, "What do you know about their so-called religion?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nothing," Virgil said. "It seems to be pretty private, but you do see some of that around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Brian Craig leaned forward and tapped his finger on the table. "Our kids both go to public schools, and I'll tell you what: I do not encourage them to hang around with anybody from this church. I just don't want those people around them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tell me why you feel like that," Virgil said. "I'm not talking about formal testimony, here. Nobody's going to write anything down. Anything helps…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The couple glanced at each other again, and then Judy Craig said, "You see people every day out here, and even if you don't talk much, you know them. Know when they have babies, for example, and about how old their kids are. Even when they don't go to school. You know what I mean?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure. I'm a small-town kid," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay. If you keep track of what's happening around the countryside, it doesn't take too many years to realize that all the people from this church are intermarrying with each other, and some of them, the girls especially, at a pretty early age. And to some pretty odd guys. You see a lot of eighteen-year-olds getting married to guys who are thirty or forty, and you wonder, how'd they get to know each other that well? When they are that young? Then Kelly gets murdered, and the Iowa police came around and asked if we knew who she dated, and we said, 'No,' because we didn't. We had no idea she was dating anybody. But every once in a while, you'd see her riding around with some older guy, somebody old enough to be her father, somebody who's already married. All members of the religion."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think, uh, these young girls are being abused?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Haven't ever seen any proof-but I wouldn't want my kids around them," Brian Craig said, unknowingly echoing the verdict of the man who'd known that Bobby Tripp was gay.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They meet on Sunday? I understand they meet in people's barns and so on."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. Not everybody's barns, just a few of them. The Floods, the Bochers, the Steinfelds. The biggest barns, all sealed up, with some heat. They meet Wednesday nights, too. Sundays in the mornings, Wednesdays after dark. Sometimes they've got something going on Fridays."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked about that for a while, and then Virgil moved on to the Tripp angle: "Had you ever seen Kelly Baker around with a boy who you thought might be gay?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Craig frowned. "Don't have many gays out here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There must be some," Virgil said. "There usually are."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I just wouldn't know that," Craig said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you know Peter Van Mann?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure, we know Pete," Craig said. "He's not gay. What'd he do?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was told he's another guy who might not care for the Bakers."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's true," Judy Craig said. "He once had a German shepherd who bit Louise Baker pretty bad. He paid for the doctor and everything, but then the Bakers sued him for pain and suffering, and they won. He had to sell off some land to pay up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She wasn't disfigured or anything, was she? I didn't notice anything," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, not much of that. I think it was just pain and suffering," Craig said. "They saw their chance, and they took it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Craig, on his way back to the barn, walked Virgil to his truck and said, "If you really need to find out what's going on in that church, it's gonna be tough. I don't know anybody around here who really walked away from it. It's all the same families, and they stick to it." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil went down the road to the Van Mann place, and saw a lonely figure walking up a snow-packed drive, followed by a black Labrador retriever. Virgil turned in, and he and the man got to the farmyard at the same time. Virgil hopped out of his truck, introduced himself, and Van Mann said, "Come on in. Come on, Jack."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They settled at the kitchen table, with Jack lying by Virgil's feet, where he could smell Virgil's pants.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Peter Van Mann was a widower farmer, a tall, thin bald man with gold-rimmed glasses and a way of looking at Virgil from the corner of his green eyes. From their chairs, they could look out through a bay window, at a tree with a tire swing. His kids had all gone out to California, Van Mann said, one after another, looking for jobs in computers. "They won't be coming back, except to sell off the property when I croak," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Gets dark here in the winter," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And quiet and cold," Van Mann said. "I think it was the quiet that pushed them out. I've always liked it, the quiet and cold both."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 His wife, he said, had died of cancer, which he suspected was brought on by farm chemicals used when she was a girl, after World War II. "I can remember when the mosquito sprayers used to come, and blast everything with DDT. We'd walk around in a cloud of it, sometimes. Now I think we're paying for it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He didn't have much to say about the Bakers, except that their lawsuit against him had been a fraud. "The thing is, there's a lot of asparagus that grows in the ditches, and Louise Baker was out cutting a mess of it. Old Pat, that was my dog back then, went after her. I don't know why, he'd never bit anybody before. I suspect she threw a rock at him or hit him with a stick or something, though she says he just came at her. Anyway, she got bit, no doubt about that. Mabel Gentry, she was the rural route carrier out here then-this was years ago, maybe twenty years now, all the kids were still here-carried her down to her house, and then her old man took her to the doc. I paid for that, a couple hundred bucks, she had stitches and pills and so on. Then they sued. This was back when farming times was pretty bad. When they won, I had to sell forty acres to pay them off. Land prices was nowhere at the time. That same land is worth five or six times as much now. Pains me every time I see somebody on it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So why was it a fraud?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, it wasn't exactly, but you know what I mean," Van Mann said. "Things happen when you're farming. She was bit, and it hurt, but it was nothing anybody else would have thought was serious. No farmers, anyway. And sure as hell not fifty thousand dollars' worth."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No insurance?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let it slip-the liability. Like I said, things were really tough back then," Van Mann said. "This was back before gasohol."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked about bad times for a couple of minutes, and Van Mann said that he didn't know much about the church, but that his father had said that it was "bad business" and wouldn't talk about it. "They keep to themselves, and always have. They're very tight. Don't socialize with their neighbors, don't get involved in politics, never run for anything."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is there a sex thing going on in the church?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Van Mann leaned back and crossed his legs, a defensive move, but then said, "The thought has occurred to me. But I don't have any direct information."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You ever know anybody to take off? Leave the church?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Van Mann's eyes narrowed as he thought about it, and he said, "There was some talk about a woman who ran away to somewhere. Her name was Birdy, that's what I remember about it. Must have been ten or twelve years ago. Birdy Olms. I can't remember what the situation was, or even how I know about it, but it seems to me that she was going to a doc, and left the office, and when her husband came to pick her up, she was gone. They went looking for her, and it turns out she'd gotten on a bus and that was it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Never came back?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not that I know of. She was an outsider. From up north, somewhere. I don't know where Roland Olms picked her up. "\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Birdy Olms."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yup."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked the gay question, and Van Mann shook his head. "The thing about those people is that they're standoffish. If Kelly Baker knew a gay boy, he was probably a member of the church. Or maybe a relative."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She worked at a Dairy Queen in the summer."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, you see some of them working around," Van Mann said. "I think maybe the Bakers needed the money. For somebody who's been doing it as long as he has, Baker is one horseshit farmer."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 By the time Virgil left Van Mann's place, it was dark. He tried calling the newspaper again, and was told that Sullivan had already filed his copy from Mankato, and might be heading north to the Cities to spend the night.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He called Coakley as he turned onto I-90 and said, "Holiday Inn, twenty minutes?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The restaurant. See you there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He thought about that as he drove into the gathering darkness: they could have met at the restaurant, or they could have met in his room. He'd known and carefully observed a reasonably large number of women in his life, and the choice of the restaurant was significant, he thought, and in a good way. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley was back in civilian clothes, tan canvas jeans, a black blouse and deep green sweater, and her cowboy boots. Virgil had found a booth well away from the three that were already occupied, and she slid in across from him and said, "I can't do it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Really."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She leaned toward him and said, "I want to, but I just can't jump into bed with somebody, cold. I've been thinking about it all afternoon."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So have I," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And what do you think?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil leaned back and closed his eyes and said, "You know what? It's been a while since I've been in bed with a woman, and I miss it. I'm just… needy enough… that I would have gone for it, and tried to patch the holes later. You are a seriously attractive woman. But this is better. We need to talk a lot more. Then jump in bed."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Deal," she said, and she smiled, and the smile lit up the booth-and Virgil's heart as well. But then, his heart wasn't all that hard to light up. "God, you made that easy. Is it because you're generous, or because you're slick?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hey, I'm from Marshall. There aren't any slick guys from Marshall."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I once knew a slick guy from there," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Now you're lying," Virgil said. "There are no slick guys from Marshall."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, no, really-his name was Richard Reedy-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Richard," Virgil said, laughing. "I know Richard. He was two years ahead of me. My God, you're right. He used to wax his hair, so he had this little pointy thing that stuck up from his forehead, like the crest on a cardinal. He used to wear sport coats to school when he didn't have to."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I saw him up in the Cities a couple of years ago," she said. "He wears these plutonium suits and his hair is still waxed and he's got one of those little telephone clip things on his ear, like he's expecting a call from his agent," she said. "Like his movie is being made."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They both had a nice laugh, and then Virgil said, "All right. Now. Whoops, here comes a waiter. Shoo him away."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She did and Virgil went on: "I'm getting more and more of a feeling that there's something seriously wrong with this church. And that it might involve underage sex on a pretty wide scale. How underage, I don't know."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Farm girls, not all of them, but some of them, can grow up pretty early. Sex is no big mystery if you grow up on a farm with animals," Coakley said. "And when you're out in the country, you spend quite a bit of time on your own, if you want. It's easy to sneak off with a boyfriend."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded. "Get a blanket out in a cornfield and you're good."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Except you get corn cuts all over your butt, and itch like crazy," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They looked at each other and laughed again, and then she said, "If it's under age seventeen, I think people would look past it. If it's under age thirteen, we could get a lynch mob going."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Think about the fact that Kelly Baker was pretty badly abused, in a hard-core way, a porno-movie way," Virgil said. "Whips. Multiple partners, possibly simultaneously, according to the Iowa ME. And that she'd been previously abused in the same way, and that nobody can find any sign that she was hooking, or any partners."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil, that's really ugly, what you're thinking," Coakley said, dead sober.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. It is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He told her about trying to call Sullivan, based on the interview with Tripp's friend Jay Wenner, that she already knew about. "These farm guys, Craig and Van Mann, kept coming back to the fact that these church people are really tight with each other, and don't much socialize with outsiders. If this gay kid was a friend of Kelly Baker, then he's probably a church kid, and he probably knows everything she did. About everything. We need to find him. We need to talk to Sullivan, soon as we can."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He's probably with his friend up there. You think we should try to track him down?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, they told me he's working tomorrow, so we can probably get him early tomorrow. Can't do much more tonight, anyway," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Have you thought about the possibility of spying on one of these church meetings?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He smiled: "Yes."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm up for that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It'd have to be one of your guys you absolutely trust," Virgil said. "It's possible that Crocker was actually planted on the department by the church… If you're involved in some kind of mass child abuse thing, even if it's religion-based, you're going to be curious about what the local law enforcement agency is up to."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "It'll be someone we can trust. Me."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He nodded. "Okay. We'll be like ninjas, black ghosts slipping unseen across the Minnesota countryside."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Probably get eaten by hogs," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Minnesota ninjas fear no hogs," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And what else?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We need to track down a woman named Birdy Olms," Virgil said. He explained. "With a name like that, I think we've got a chance."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll get on that. And your DNA sample is at your lab. Jeanette took it up, and said they whined at her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, well, I got my boss to jack them up," Virgil said. "The problem is, everybody wants DNA. DNA for everything. We're jumping the line, which pisses everybody off."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We've got four dead," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But if the DNA pans out, we'll have a hammerlock on Spooner. She grew up in the church, but she's already stepped away from them. If we can get her with a murder charge, we might be able to open her up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She thought about that, and then said, "They've been out there for a long time, this church. I wonder what they'd do if they thought it was about to come down on them?"\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 11\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Patrick Sullivan, the reporter, woke Virgil at seven o'clock in the morning: "Hope I didn't wake you up. I just found your message."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I need to talk to you," Virgil said. "Are you at home?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Right now, I am. I need to get cleaned up and head into work by eight," Sullivan said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll be there in half an hour," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He got cleaned up in a rush, stood for an extra minute in a hot shower, storing up some warmth, dressed, and headed out. The predawn was bitterly cold, the dry air like a knife against his face; and dark, as the season rolled downhill to the winter solstice, and the days were hardly long enough to remember. Sullivan had given him simple directions, and Virgil was at the curb outside his house twenty-nine minutes after he'd gotten out of bed, street-lights twinkling down the way.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan lived on the second floor of a stately white-and-teal Victorian on Landward Avenue. When Virgil arrived, the reporter was in the driveway, chipping frost off the windshield of a three-year-old Jeep Cherokee.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When did you get in?" Virgil asked, as they headed up the walk to his apartment. If he'd driven down from the Cities, he wouldn't have been chipping frost.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I came back late last night. I was afraid if I stayed over, I'd get jammed up in traffic. What's up?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A couple more questions about Tripp," Virgil said. Sullivan led the way through the front door and up an old wooden staircase with a polished mahogany railing curling around a halfway landing.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not bad," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The price is right," Sullivan said. He unlocked the door of his apartment. "Up in the Cities, this place would cost me fifteen hundred more'n I'm paying here." He had three rooms-living room, bedroom, and kitchen, with a bath off the bedroom. "Microwave some coffee?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Fine," Virgil said. He took a chair at the kitchen table, and when Sullivan brought the cups over, took one, and Sullivan sat opposite. "So."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "There's a lot going on out there," Virgil said. "Kelly Baker, these other killings, they're all hooked together, I think. We've been talking to people, and one guy who should know tells us that Kelly hooked up Tripp with another gay guy. Probably somebody she knew from this church she belonged to."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And you want to know if I know who he is," Sullivan said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "In a nutshell."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't," Sullivan said. "I'd be a little surprised if Bob was sexually active."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if he kept it from you? I mean, this would be something he might not even want to admit to himself, much less to somebody outside the relationship," Virgil said. "Since whoever he is was a friend of Kelly's, we wonder if you ever saw a guy hanging around with her, who might've given you a look…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan stared down into his coffee for a minute, then said, "There's something…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil took a sip of coffee, waiting.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I didn't hang around with Bob in public. He wasn't ready for people to know. But I ran into him once at the Dairy Queen, and he and Baker were with another man. The other guy gave off this vibration… I didn't remember until you asked."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You know him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. He was a real tall guy," Sullivan said. "I mean, six-seven or six-eight. Not real good-looking, but interesting-looking, like somebody had chipped him out of wood. Abe Lincoln."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How old?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan fingered the rim of his ear, thinking, then said, "I can't say for sure, but I'd say, older than Bobby. Twenties. Probably not thirty. Dark hair, wore it long. Not hippie-long-farmer-long."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Huh," Virgil said. "Thank you." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 That was what Sullivan had, and Virgil stood up to leave. "Give me one thing for my story," Sullivan said. He reached over to the kitchen counter and picked up a narrow, half-used reporter's notebook and a ballpoint. "Anything good."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil considered, then said, "We think we've linked the Baker killing to the murders of Jacob Flood and Bob Tripp. I can't tell you more than that. I will say that we've collected a variety of evidence, which is now being processed by the BCA lab, and we could get a break in a day or two. Chemistry takes time. But-I would like you to attribute this to an unnamed source, if you can. If not… I could take some heat."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can do that." Sullivan scribbled in the notebook. "What about the evidence involving Bob in a homosexual affair?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We don't know that there was one," Virgil said. "I guess you can't libel a dead man, but what's the point in saying that, until it leads somewhere?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Sullivan nodded and closed the notebook: "So-why are you looking into it? If it doesn't matter?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The sex in itself doesn't matter, though it might technically be a crime, if there's a disparity of ages, and depending on when Bob's birthday was."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, horseshit…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm just sayin'," Virgil said. "But the main thing is, if this other guy was tight with Baker, he might know what happened to her, and who might have done it. You've given me enough information that I think I can find him. And if he is older, and if he was involved with Tripp when he was a minor, then we might have a handy little sex-crime tool kit for getting him to talk."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But you're not going to mess with him just because he's gay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Look-I really don't care what people do with each other, as long as everybody consents. And they're old enough to consent," Virgil said. "I've got more important things to think about. Like what to have for lunch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I knew you were a secret liberal," Sullivan said. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Out in his truck Virgil called Van Mann, the farmer whose dog had bitten Louise Baker. "I've got a question for you, which I'd appreciate it if you could keep it under your hat."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can do that," Van Mann said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm looking for a guy who may be a member of the church…" He relayed Sullivan's description.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's probably Harvey Loewe," Van Mann said. "He lives a couple of miles down south of me. He's got an old farmhouse more or less across the road from his folks' place. His folks are Joe and Marsha Loewe. Harvey's probably twenty-six or twenty-seven. He would have been God's gift to the Northwest High basketball team, if he'd gone to public school."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is Harvey married?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, I don't believe so. Never really seen him with a woman," Vann Mann said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Thank you. And listen, keep it-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Under my hat. I'll do that." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil called coakley: "You up?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not entirely," she said. "I still got the boys to get out of here, and I've got to figure out my word for the day. Hang on-okay, it's 'porcine,' which means related to pigs, or piglike. I have to use it five times, in context."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to go interview the homosexual guy who had the affair with Bobby Tripp. I need to spot his place, and-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is he porcine?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not as far as I know. But if you could look him up…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. And I'm coming," she said. "Give me forty-five minutes."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I thought you might be," Virgil said. "Bring a gun with you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You think there might be trouble?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, but we're cops, and I think somebody should have a gun."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil went by the Yellow Dog for some pancakes. Jacoby came over with a cup of coffee and asked if there was anything new. "Not at the moment," Virgil said. "But we're pushing ahead."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let me know," Jacoby said. He dropped the cup of coffee on the table and went to get the pancakes.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Ten seconds later, a short, thin man with a waxed mustache stood up from the booth where he'd been reading the Star Tribune, folded it, looked around, and walked down and slipped into the booth opposite Virgil.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm Rich," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded: "Good for you. Hard to get that way, with all the high taxes."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The man half-smiled, showing brown teeth. He leaned forward on his elbows and said, "I know something that might be of interest in your investigation."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm listening," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is there any kind of reward?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded again: "The knowledge that you've helped your fellow man."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was afraid of that," the man said. His furtiveness seemed to be a built-in part of his personality, Virgil decided. "Anyhow. People are talking. They're saying you're looking at all these church people, out there in the sticks. And they might have been doing dirty by this Kelly Baker girl. That got me to thinking."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "We'd be very interested in anything about Kelly Baker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not exactly about her. But I work down at the Wal-Mart. You know where that is?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I do."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So. I'm the photo technician. I used to run the print-making machine and so on, back when we developed film, and I got to know who was who in the local photography community. One of these church people out there, his name is Karl Rouse, this is back in the film days, he used to buy a load of Polaroid film. I mean, a load. You know what I mean?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A lot," Virgil said. He took a sip of coffee.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A load. And when people bought that much Polaroid, unless they were a real estate agent or something, I'd get ideas of what they were taking pictures of. You know?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay," Virgil said. "You ever see any evidence of that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, not exactly. But I can tell you, it's a heck of a lot cheaper to shoot with a film camera and have us develop it. And he did that, too. He was a regular shutterbug, taking church pictures and so on. So I'm asking myself, 'How come we're only getting half of his business? The non-Polaroid part?'"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But no real indication…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. I can tell you, when digital came in, he was first in line to buy a photo printer, and he still buys a lot of paper from us. Keeps really busy. Anyhow, I thought you'd like to know that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I'll keep it in mind," Virgil said. "But I'll tell you, there's no Rouse in this investigation so far."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Rich was disappointed, but said, "Well, you oughta take a look. I got an instinct for these things, and I think something was going on there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jacoby came back and said, "Hey, Rich. You find a clue?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe," Rich said. He slid out of the booth. "I gotta get going, I'm due at work. But: think about that. I believe it could be important."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What was that?" Jacoby asked, when Rich was out the door.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nothing much, I'm afraid," Virgil said. "Another guy trying to help out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jacoby dropped his voice: "Not so much a guy, as the village idiot."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil picked Coakley up at her house, a pleasant wood-and-brick sixties rambler. She met him at the door, invited him in, led him through a kitchen that smelled like toast and peanut butter and jam, to a tiny office. "I've got Harvey Loewe's house spotted on Google," she said. She touched the mouse, and a satellite shot popped up on the screen. "He's on Twentieth Street, way down here in the southwest. Right…" She reached out and pushed the scale on the map, then tapped the screen with a fingertip. "Here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The picture had been taken in the summer, in a raking, early-morning light, and Loewe's house, which was white, stood out clearly in the green fields that ran right up to it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No yard," Virgil said. "Not even a front yard. No outbuildings."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's like with Crocker. It's an old vacant farmhouse," she said. "Some of them get burned by the fire department, but some of them aren't so bad. You can live in them, with a little work, if you're handy. Most farm kids are."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "His folks are right around there someplace," Virgil said. There was nothing exactly across the road, but there were single houses both east and west of Loewe's, and both were across the road, and appeared to be inhabited. "I'd rather not have them know we're talking to their kid, you know?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On the way out, Virgil detailed his talk with Sullivan.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you trust him?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, not entirely," Virgil said. "He seems like a good enough guy, but he is a reporter, and they are weasels, just by their nature. Though I don't know what he'd be hiding from us."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe had a sexual relationship with Tripp that he'd rather not talk about," Coakley suggested. "Talking about it could cause him some trouble. You know, with his boyfriend."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's possible. But I still don't see where it'd take us. I think Tripp was the end of a string of information, and Sullivan would be even further out. We need to follow the string into the source, not further out." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They found Loewe taping 3M window-sealing plastic over his kitchen windows. He saw them coming, met them at the door. They told him what they were doing, and a transient little muscle spasm seemed to pass over his face, and the corners of his mouth turned down, but he was polite: "I don't know how I can help, but come in."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He was a tall man, who did look a bit like Lincoln, thin but hard, with knobby shoulders and hands, and big, square, slightly yellow teeth. His hair was as long as Virgil's, and he was wearing low-rise jeans, a purple cotton shirt, and loafers. "Putting this plastic up-the house has got no insulation in the walls whatsoever. I put in sixteen inches of fiberglass in the attic, and when I get the windows sealed, I can at least keep the place warm without going broke."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You own it, or gonna buy it?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nah, probably not," he said. "I'm thinking of moving up to the Cities, after next fall, go back to school."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Good idea," Coakley said. "What'd you be taking?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Studio art, at the U," he said. "I'm a painter, when it isn't too cold. So: how can I help, and why me?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley said, "We're looking at these murders-Flood, Tripp, Crocker. And Kelly Baker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 His eyebrows went up. "They're connected?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's what we're trying to find out," Virgil said. "We've heard-we're keeping our sources pretty close to our chest, and we'll do the same with you-but we heard that you were friends with Baker and with Bobby Tripp."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe sort of leaned back, the way people do when they've heard something they don't like. He didn't answer for a minute, then said, "Yeah, I was. I talked to the Iowa police a couple of times. Nothing ever came of it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're coming at it from a different angle," Virgil said. "Because we also know about the relationship between Tripp and Kelly. We're wondering if Kelly ever told you about that relationship, or if Tripp did. If there was something in there that could cause Tripp to kill Flood. Did Flood have some sort of abusive relationship with Kelly?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I wouldn't know about that," Loewe said. "Jake could be a jerk, that's for sure. I just wonder if there wasn't a fight between him and Bobby, and it got a little too serious?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil shook his head. "If there'd been a fight, it would have shown up on Tripp-he would have been bruised or cut up or something. Flood was a big guy, and solid. We think Tripp snuck up on him, hit him with a ball bat."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Mmm, boy, I don't see him doing that. He was a pretty tough guy, football player and all, but he wasn't mean," Loewe said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think he was gay?" Coakley asked. She asked it with a motherly, understanding undertone that gave her thought away.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe flinched: "Gay? Doesn't seem likely. He was a big football guy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's been suggested that you may have had a relationship with him," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe took a step back, but didn't say anything for a moment, then, instead of saying, "No," he asked, "Who said that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Look, we're keeping all of this very close. And we don't even need to know whether or not you did, because that's private, and I don't see how it could affect the case. But: we need to know what Kelly did, what caused her to be murdered, and why Tripp would murder somebody in return, and then be murdered himself… and on down the line. Do not forget that there's still a murderer running loose."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You don't think I'm involved…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know," Virgil said. "Are you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe turned, walked away from them, picked up a roll of the plastic window sheeting. "I'm not going to talk to you anymore. This is crazy-I don't know what happened to anybody." His voice was climbing in pitch: he was scared, and Virgil decided to push it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think the killings might have anything to do with your church? We've noticed a lot of connections there-you know. Kelly Baker, Flood, even Crocker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The church? What connection could it have to the church?" he asked. "I think there might be some connection because everything happened in the same place… but not the church. Look, I really don't want to talk about this anymore. But I'll tell you: I have nothing to do with this. Any of it. I was freaked when Kelly Baker died, and I was freaked when Jake Flood got killed, and even more freaked when B.J. was killed."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did you ever know a woman named Birdy Olms?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Birdy? What does she have to do with it? She took off years ago. Back when I was a kid."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Any idea where she went?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nobody does," Loewe said. "I guess that's how she planned it. She's gone."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil looked at him for a couple of beats, and then asked, "You don't have any idea why Kelly Baker was killed? Your friend Kelly."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm not even sure she was murdered-the Iowa cops didn't seem all that sure of it. Maybe… it was an accident."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She'd been pretty severely abused," Virgil said. "So that almost certainly makes it murder. If they were older than she was, the killers, that makes it statutory rape, a crime. If she died in the course of a crime, then it's murder. Everybody involved, and everybody involved with hiding the killers, is going to prison for thirty years, no parole. No art school, nothing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay, that's it. I'm done," Loewe said, but his voice didn't seem to Virgil to contain as much anger as it did fear. "I didn't have anything to do with Kelly. We knew each other: that's all. Now, please leave. Please."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Wait a minute, Harvey. We're investigating three murders, for Christ's sakes. We're not trying to inconvenience you-we're trying to find a killer. And there's still a killer out there, trying to shut people up. You wanna be on that list?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And Coakley said, "Harvey-we know about you and Bobby. We really don't want to embarrass you. And we're not embarrassed about gay people; one of the people who's helping us on this case is gay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Who'd that be?" Loewe asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, we can't say."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So you're making it up," Loewe said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll tell you, as a police officer, that I'm not," Coakley said. "What we need to know is, if you were close to Bobby-we won't even ask you about sex-but if you were close to him… do you have any idea of why he'd go off on Jake Flood?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We think it's something he learned not long ago," Virgil said, "because if he'd known it all along, he would have done something sooner."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe looked down at the floor, as if trying to make up his mind.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil prodded him: "Bobby was murdered, not out of revenge, but because he knew something. Jim Crocker was killed because he knew something. We need to know what that was."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe backed up and sat down in a chair and said, "You can't tell anybody."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We won't, unless we absolutely have to-if we're required to in court," Coakley said. "I tell you that last part so I won't be lying to you. It could come out that way, but that's the only way. And we'll do everything we can to avoid that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, God, it'll come out," Loewe said. And, "I've got to get out of here anyway."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tell us, Harvey," Virgil said. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe said, "I really felt close to Bobby. And I want to tell you that our relationship didn't start until he was eighteen, almost nineteen. He was a good guy, and I don't say that because of our relationship. He was a good guy with everybody."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I buy that. He was a good guy," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe said, "When Kelly got killed, nobody knew anything. But, she was in the church, and the word got around pretty fast, about the sex and all. Bobby had been around with her quite a bit, and they'd gotten pretty close. They used to talk a lot, about everything. Ah, jeez… we were together once, and I told him about the sex. But he already knew."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He already knew what? That she had a sexual relationship with somebody?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. She told him. She told him that things got rough, sometimes, and that she kinda liked it, I guess. She didn't tell him everything, though. I told him… the rest of it. From the autopsy report-that got around the church pretty fast. About how a bunch of guys were on her. About how somebody had whipped her and all of that. Everybody in the church knew about it, I think from her parents, or maybe her uncle. He was really freaked out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Had Bobby had a sexual relationship with her?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, no. Kelly knew he was gay. She actually introduced us… Kelly and I knew each other for a long time, and she knew I was that way. But I think they both felt a little bit like sex freaks, him being a gay football guy, and she because of the sexual things she did."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So he freaked out," Virgil said. "But how did that get him to Jacob Flood?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I did that, too, I guess," Loewe said. He looked everywhere but at Coakley and Virgil. "The last time I saw him, he asked me if Jake Flood knew Kelly. I said, 'Well, yeah. They're in the church.' He asked if Jake ever hung around Kelly. I don't know why I said it, but I said, 'They know each other, for sure.' Then he said that Jake had come into the elevator, with his shirt off, and he had a Statue of Liberty tattoo on his stomach. I said, 'Yeah, he does. It goes right down to his…" He glanced at Coakley. "… You know, down there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil: "And he said?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He said Kelly used to… have rough sex with somebody named Liberty. And I said, 'Maybe it was him. People who know him call him Liberty sometimes.' You know, I was joking."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Did people really call him that?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A few," Loewe said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said to Coakley, "On the drawing of the statue, the one I got from Tripp's backpack, there was a long oval, drawn in pencil. You remember that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It was an erect penis," Virgil said. He turned back to Loewe: "Did he say anything about taking the information to the police?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe shook his head. "No, he never said anything about that. I think, you know, he thought that if he told anybody about all that, about him and Kelly, that it'd all come out. About him being gay, and all. About me being gay. So… I didn't think he'd do anything. It never really… occurred to me."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I want you to tell me the truth, here, Harvey," Virgil said. "Does this sex thing have anything to do with the church? I mean, okay, you're gay, so you're out of it. But a lot of church guys are hooking up with young women. Real young women. Is there some sort of thing where the church says the marriage age, in the eyes of God, is younger than, you know, the regular age?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, no, nothing like that," Loewe said. "The people in the church are close, so they all know each other, and I guess guys are looking for girls who share… church stuff. I don't share it so much anymore, I'm thinking about getting out. But, the church is the church."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So you know Emmett Einstadt?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Everybody knows Emmett. He's like… the pope of our church."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And there's no kind of organized sex."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's a church," Loewe said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked about it a bit more, and Virgil said, "You're going to have to come in and make a formal statement, Harvey. This is important stuff."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, God."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Doesn't have to be right this minute. But we're going to need it, sooner or later."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You said it wouldn't have to come out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That was before we knew how important it is. Maybe the information won't get us anywhere, and you won't have to. But if it breaks this case, then you will." Virgil slipped a business card out of his pocket, dropped it on the kitchen counter. "If you think of anything, call me. Don't talk to anyone else about it. We were serious about there being a killer out there." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Loewe followed them to the door, said, "Please help me out. Don't tell anybody."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They left him standing in the doorway, and when he shut the door behind them, Coakley said, pulling on her gloves, "I feel a little bad about Harvey."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He should have talked to the Iowa cops a long time ago," Virgil said. "It might have taken them to Flood. Then there'd be three guys still alive."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not if he didn't know that Kelly was having sex with Liberty when he was talking to the Iowa people," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right. Maybe he didn't," Virgil conceded. "But maybe he did. I think he was lying to us, a little bit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I just hope he doesn't do anything awful," Coakley said. They looked back at the house and saw a sheet of plastic move in the window.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What do we do from here?" Coakley asked. She'd been wearing a Fargo-style watch cap, and now she took it off, tossed it in the backseat, and shook her hair out.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Surveillance. They'll be having church services tonight. We watch Flood's place, and we watch Baker's, and we follow them to wherever the service is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That'd be tough out here," she said. They both looked across the flat, snow-covered fields; you could see a car a mile away. With lights at night, maybe three or four miles.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll make some calls-see if I can get a highway patrol plane to park over the Floods' place, track them from a distance," Virgil said. "They can call us on the ground. We could wait in Battenberg or wherever."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You think you can get it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think so. I'd have to talk to my boss, but the dimensions of this thing are getting to be interesting," Virgil said. "He'll go for it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It is interesting," Coakley said, "but I doubt that it'll do me much good in the next election."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You can live with it," Virgil said. "If what I think is going on, is going on…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can live with it," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He started the truck and eased out of Loewe's driveway, turned left, back toward town. "The thing is," Virgil said, as they drove along, "if we get the DNA back from the lab tomorrow, we may be close to finished-if we can show that Spooner killed Crocker, and that closes the chain of murders."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But we're not done," Coakley protested. "Flood is dead, but there were more people involved with Kelly Baker-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's an Iowa case," Virgil said. "We send them a file with what we think."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, come on, Virgil," she said. And apparently without thinking about it-or maybe she did, he thought later, because he sometimes tended toward cynicism, or at least the study of human calculation-she reached over with her inboard hand and put it on his thigh. "This is our case now. Iowa's going nowhere with it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She pulled her hand back, leaving behind a hand-sized warm spot; and she still seemed unaware of the casual intimacy. Virgil tended to think that women were hardly ever unaware of even the most casual intimacy; they had intimacy detectors more powerful than a rat's cheese detector, although, he decided, the analogy might not be precise.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So we agree on that," he said. "In fact, I was planning to kill most of the rest of the day hanging out, waiting for the DNA to come in. But now I'm thinking I'll go talk to Alma Flood. I'd like to catch her without her father around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She patted him on the thigh again: "Do that. Check the plane first. And call the lab about the DNA, see where they're at. I'm going to get some of the boys who know about the church, get a list of names, and run every one of them through the feds. Maybe something will pop up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They came up to a stop sign and Virgil said, "I hate this truck for this. The guy who invented consoles must've been some kind of uber-nerd."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He put the truck in park, reached an arm around her shoulder, pulled her as close as the console would allow, and kissed her. She saw it coming and went with it, and when they ran out of air, he backed off a few inches, then kissed her again, and when she sank into him, he twisted a bit more so he could cup her far breast in his left hand. She went with that, too, though only for a few seconds, before rolling away from him, and she said, "Mmmm."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, hell, it's a start," he said, putting the truck back in gear. "I've never kissed a sheriff before."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Probably never felt one up, either," she said, patting her hair back into place. "Not that I didn't like it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He thought about a wisecrack, but instantly suppressed it, going instead for a sincere-sounding, and possibly shy-sounding, "I wouldn't have… characterized it like that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She squinted at him, one eye blue, one eye green, and then, he thought, bought it. If you can sell sincerity to a woman, you're halfway home. Not to be cynical about it. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil called the BCA office as soon as he got a cell phone signal, talked to Davenport. "You fly around in that plane more than any six other guys," Davenport said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't want to fly in it," Virgil said. "I'll be on the ground. We'll send along one of Lee's deputies to watch one of the houses, maybe the Floods, or this Einstadt guy, see where the meeting is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I sense an emotional resonance in the way you said 'Lee,' " Davenport said. "I heard she's a looker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's correct," Virgil said. "I plan to further explore those aspects of the case."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, yeah, I don't want to hear it," Davenport said. "Well, actually I do, but some other time."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Wouldn't be good right now," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She's sitting right next to you, right?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil nodded at his phone. "Yup."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You know, if the DNA comes through, we could just let the rest of it slide."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Lucas, there are girls in this church who are much younger than your daughter," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, man," Davenport said. "Where do you want the plane?" \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They settled that, and he got Davenport to switch him up to the DNA lab, where he talked to a tech. The lab was still processing the DNA from the hair taken from Spooner's couch, but, the tech said, she'd have something to tell Virgil by noon the next day.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil got off and said to Coakley, "Noon tomorrow. I do believe we'll have Miz Spooner in jail by two o'clock."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That could crack it," Coakley said. She patted him on the thigh again.\par
