\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 16\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Early the next morning, Spooner drove over to Einstadt's house and caught him at breakfast. "They say they're going to investigate further, but they're not going to charge me at this time," she told him. "They came over and searched my house, and took my computer, but I'd cleaned the place out and cleaned the computer out, so there's nothing to find. We're okay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt was gnawing through a six-inch stack of buttermilk pancakes and bacon, soaked in a crimson-colored berry syrup that looked like blood. He chewed with his mouth half-open, while he thought about it, then said, "What'd the state guy tell you? Flowers?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I didn't see him after the morning. And he didn't tell me anything," Spooner said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "His truck wasn't at the Holiday overnight," Einstadt said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're watching him? What for?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "My boys check around every once in a while, just to see where he is, and who he's talking to. He spent the afternoon talking to Coakley, if that's what they were doing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if they weren't talking?" Spooner asked. "What if they were in there fucking like bunnies? So what? They're adults, and they're allowed. But you're sneaking around watching them, they're gonna catch you at it, and that won't be good. It's time to lie low, Emmett. That's all we can do."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Shooting Jim is what you call lying low?" he asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If I hadn't shot him, they'd have strung you up by now, and not by your neck," she said. "You owe me, and everybody in the Spirit owes me. Jim was a loose cannon, and he was going to take us all with him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt scowled and said, "We're not stupid, Kathleen. We're already doing it. Lying low. There won't be any spirit pools for a few weeks. Everything will stay private and quiet."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's all I wanted to know," she said, pushing herself to her feet. "I will still be taking the Fischl brothers to school. I'm sure they won't mind."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt held up a finger. "About this Flowers guy. He's stirring things up. Junior had an idea about that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, God help me," Spooner said. "If that boy were any dumber, he'd have to be watered twice a week."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Shut up. He's a good boy. Listen to this: what if Flowers walked into a holdup at Loren's?" Einstadt peered at her. "What if he got a tip from one of his pals down at the Yellow Dog that Loren knew something, and he goes over there and walks right into a holdup and gets his ass shot dead?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Are you… you mean, by me? A fake holdup?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, since you're the one with all the experience. Loren would say it was a couple of bikers in an old Chevy, and they took off, and that's all he knows."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner sat down again, clenched her hands on the table, leaned forward. "I'll say this as serious as I can, Emmett. When I turned myself in to Coakley, she called Flowers. He came down and they both asked questions, and they both knew everything that was going on. And there were two other cops listening in, and they all knew it, too. This isn't one guy figuring everything out, like in a movie. They all know what's going on. You'd have to kill the whole sheriff's department to wipe out what Flowers knows. And if Flowers gets shot, they'll be all over us, like red ants. Just don't do anything. We're okay right now. Stop watching them. Don't do anything."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt had finished all but a half pancake. He picked it up by its edge, sopped up all the loose syrup and bacon grease, rolled it, and stuffed it in his mouth, chewed for a while, then said, "It really ain't what Flowers knows. It's what he can figure out. He's not some country cop. So, okay, for now-you got good points. But the situation could change." VIRGIL GOT UP a little later than he had been, took his cell phone into the bathroom. Davenport called, of course, just as he'd finished smearing shaving cream over his face. He wiped half of it off, answered, and Davenport said, "The call went to a Lenore Mackey in Omaha."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil got his notebook and wrote down the information that Davenport had, and said, "Lucy McCain, Lenore Mackey. That's her. I'm going to Omaha. You want to call the Nebraska guys and tell them I'm coming?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can do that," Davenport said. "Drive safely."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil called Coakley and told her where he was going, packed up, and headed out. There was really no efficient way to get from New Ulm to Omaha. He went cross-country, over a web of state highways, until he got to I-29 outside Sioux City, Iowa, and then south, the time marked more by the music than by the terrain, which was all the same, country houses and snow, bare trees and rolling prairie; and Billy Joe Shaver, "Georgia on a Fast Train"; "The Devil Made Me Do It the First Time (The Second Time I Done It on My Own)"; James McMurtry, "Choctaw Bingo"; Don Williams, "Tulsa Time." Like that, until he crossed the Missouri River bridge north of Council Bluffs and rolled down into Omaha.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 In addition to singing along, he spoke to a Lieutenant Joe Murphy from the Nebraska Patrol's investigative division, who told him how to get to Lenore Mackey's house, which was northwest of Omaha's downtown area. They agreed to meet at a pizza place off Saddle Creek Road, a half-mile from Mackey's. MURPHY WAS a chunky, black-haired, crew-cut guy with a skeptical cast to his face, maybe a bit annoyed to be on escort duty for a guy from Minnesota. They were sitting in a booth waiting for a pepperoni and sausage, and Murphy said, "So if she tells you to go away, you turn around and drive five hours back."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If I can talk to her for two minutes, I can probably get her to talk for half an hour," Virgil said. "I didn't want to call ahead, because I was afraid that she'd go on vacation somewhere."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Murphy looked at his watch: "I cruised by her place and didn't see anybody around. She might be working."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So, I sit," Virgil said. "You could go on and do whatever you're doing. I could give you a ring when she shows up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, the boss told me to stick with you. He's pals with your boss up in St. Paul. So, we both sit-if she's not there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She wasn't.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Her house was an uninflected, rectangular white rambler with a one-car garage at the west end. They knocked on her door, without much hope-the afternoon was moving on, and there wasn't a light anywhere in the house. No answer. On the other hand, there was a single letter in the mailbox, a bill, which meant that the mail hadn't been turned off, and had been picked up recently.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They found a spot down the block and sat in Virgil's truck, engine running, listening to the radio. Murphy liked Billy Joel and Paul Simon, which seemed Omaha-like, to Virgil, and was all right with him, for a while, anyway. Virgil outlined the problem in Homestead, and they talked awhile about their careers, and sports. Murphy's father worked for an Omaha insurance company, and he'd lived in Maryland when he was in school, and had been a lacrosse player.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil wasn't too interested in lacrosse, which sounded to him like French hockey, but Murphy corrected him, told him how Native Americans invented it, and then went on an extended riff about the game. Virgil had played football, basketball, and baseball in high school, and enjoyed team sports, and when Murphy finally shut up, he said, "Well, I sort of wish we'd had that in Marshall. Sounds like a good game."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He said that for diplomatic reasons, since it still sounded like French hockey, and he didn't even particularly like real hockey.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They were in the car for an hour and a half before Mackey showed up. She rolled up her driveway, got out, manually lifted the door on the garage, and drove inside. A minute later, lights started coming on in the house.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How do you want to do this?" Murphy asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Straight. Get your ID out. I'll knock on the door, introduce myself, introduce you, get a foot in the door. Just let me talk…" \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Lenore Mackey opened the door, a wrinkle in her forehead-Louise Gordon's identical twin sister, still identical after thirty-five years or so. Virgil held up his ID and said, "Miz Mackey-Lenore, Lucy-I'm Virgil Flowers from the Minnesota Bureau of Criminal Apprehension, and this is Lieutenant Joe Murphy of the Nebraska State Patrol. We need to talk to you about a series of murders in Homestead, Minnesota, involving the World of Spirit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "Oh, shit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 But they got in the door, and on her couch, and she said, "I hope you tracked me through my sister, and not somebody in the church."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes, we did-we checked a phone call your sister made," Virgil said. "We really had no choice. You dropped off the face of the earth, and we seriously need to talk with you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What have they done?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil outlined the series of murders, then said, "We think the murders are essentially solved. We think Crocker and Flood were present when Baker was killed, and we think Flood was killed by Bobby Tripp because of that. Then Tripp and Crocker were killed to contain the information. We're pretty sure that Miz Spooner murdered Crocker, but we're not sure we can prove it-she has a story that's about as likely as ours."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I remember her, a little. She was around, though I didn't know her well," Mackey said. "I couldn't tell you anything about her, though."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We don't want to talk about that-we've got that figured out," Virgil said. "What happens from here, is more or less up to the prosecutors. What we're more interested in is the church. The World of Spirit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Why?" she asked, but she knew.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Because of the sex," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, boy…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't want to influence your story, so just tell us what you know about it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She looked at the two men and colored a bit, then said, "It's embarrassing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "This has pretty much gone past embarrassing," Virgil said. "There are four dead, including a young girl."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She nodded, and said, "I was twenty-six when I met Roland. I worked for a few years after I got out of high school, at the HyVee, but I could see that wasn't going anywhere, so I went to school up in Mankato, studying business systems. That's where I met Roland…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said that she never felt that she was pretty; that Roland had wooed her, and said she was. She never particularly wanted to marry a farmer, but Roland seemed nice enough. "Basically, I thought he might be my last chance, if I didn't want to wind up being an old maid somewhere. Which I probably will, now. In Omaha."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They married, moved to a farmstead down the highway from his parents' farm, and worked for Roland's parents, as well as some land he leased from a real estate company in Minneapolis. Everything went fine, she said, for about six months.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We had these friends, the Bosches, and the Waldts. Dick and Mary, Dick and Sandy. We'd go out with them, to the movies, or whatever, two or three times a week, sometimes. They had taco night at this bar, and we'd go there. Anyway, after about six months, Roland asked me what I thought about Dick Bosche, you know, whether I liked him…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The conversation widened. She liked him, but how much did she like him? After a couple of weeks, the question arose, would she be interested in sleeping with Dick Bosche? Dick had mentioned that he found her really powerfully attractive, and Roland thought Mary looked pretty good, and Mary was willing…\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So, we tried it. I have to say, Dick was more interesting than Roland, when it came to sex," Mackey said. "I wasn't that experienced, and he… liked to do things. Anyway, we went like this for a few weeks, trading off."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Then the question came up, wouldn't it be fun for the friends to get together. Like, all in the same place. They tried that.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then, they all said, wouldn't it be fun to bring in Dick and Sandy. By this time, I was really shaky about the whole thing. It was fun, but in sort of a sick-making way. I'd lie awake and think about it, and afterwards, when it was done…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She shook her head.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We don't really need all the details," Virgil said, trying to be kind. "How did it end up? Were you all together? All six of you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes. Eventually. And the guys wanted, you know, to do things together, so there'd be like two of them with one of us women, or two women with one of the guys, and they wanted us women to do things with each other so they could watch…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How long did this go on?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A year and a half. We got married in May, and then about the time it started snowing, we first got with Dick and Mary, and then, a few weeks later, Dick and Sandy. And that went on for a year. Then, they told me about the church. How the World of Spirit involved a merger of the spirit and the flesh between people… and I started figuring out that they had this whole group of people and that they passed each other around and they wanted to pass me around. To a lot of people. All the time."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's when you left?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I didn't leave right away. I argued about it, and Roland got really crazy, and he started slapping me. I mean, hard. I finally decided, this was no good, and I told him I was going to leave. He said if I left, the church would kill me, because I knew what they were doing, and the World of Law would wreck the church if they knew about it. I told him that I wouldn't tell anybody, but then Emmett Einstadt came over-he's like the big guru-and told me that once I was in, I couldn't get out. And I was in. After that, I had the feeling that they were watching me, all the time."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She said, "So I got passed around for a while."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If it was against your will, it was rape," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Right. Then I'd have to go to court and say, yes, I'd voluntarily slept with twenty different men, sometimes two at a time, sometimes with five or six or ten people watching us, and with women, but this one time, it was rape."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's a tough one," Virgil agreed. "So you ran away."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She smiled, then. "I took Roland's tax money-money he put aside to pay his taxes. He never really looked at the account, except at tax time. I cleaned it out, called my sister, told her I was going to run away. And I did. I got Roland to drive me to the doctor, which always took forever, went out the back door, got in the car with Louise, who was waiting, and we were gone. They came looking for me, they kept coming back on Louise, but she never told… In fact, she told them that she thought somebody might have killed me. They went away after that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How'd you get your name?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A dead girl. From Sleepy Eye. We were good friends with her mother, we told her what was happening, not all of it, and she gave us her driver's license and Social Security card. I came here to Omaha and got a job in business systems… like, being a secretary."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked, "Did you know a man named Rouse?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Karl Rouse? Oh, yeah. I got passed to him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Can you tell us anything about Rouse specifically? Did you have involuntary sex with him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I couldn't really say that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What was the youngest person you were involved with?" Virgil asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The wrinkle came back to her forehead. "Why? I mean, we were all about the same age. Some of the guys were a little older…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We believe that some of the people involved in the World of Spirit are very young. Children. Did you see any of that?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She hesitated, then said, "No, I didn't. But I never went to the Wednesday night services. You weren't allowed to go there until you were sanctified. I was close to being pulled in, but I never went all the way."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Do you think there might have been kids?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "On Wednesday nights. When we were doing one of those group things, the guys would talk. And sometimes, they talked about the women they'd been with, and I got the impression that some of them might have been younger. I never knew exactly what they were talking about, if it was seventeen or thirteen, but they were… new to sex. And these guys were breaking them in. They'd talk about that, breaking them in. Same with young boys. The women would break them in."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You don't know specifically how young?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. I never actually saw any of them. They were pretty secretive."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil looked at Murphy, who shrugged. No help. Back to Mackey. "Would you like to go back to your real name?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not if that would help them find me. I really was pretty scared. I still am."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil explained the problem: that they knew that children were being abused, but that the system was so guarded that there was no way to get enough information to get a search warrant. "We need to find a way to break into the circle. Once we're inside, we've got tools we can use to break out everybody."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She was shaking her head. "They won't talk about each other. If they get caught, they'll just take it. You'll put some of them away, but they'll never talk about each other."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We've got to do something," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can't," she said. "I've got a decent life going here. I've got a boyfriend. If he found out… I'm sorry."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked to her for a half hour more, but she wouldn't budge.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Out on the steps, Murphy said, "Sorry about that. What're you going to do?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm going to drive five hours back to Minnesota and think about it." HE WAS BACK in Homestead at 10:30. At ten, rolling east on I-90, he called Coakley. "We need to talk. Things didn't work out real well in Omaha."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But that was Birdy?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, but she's not going to be much help. She doesn't know for sure about any young people. Listen, I don't want to talk on the cell phone about this."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll see you in a half hour at the Holiday-in the bar."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "In the bar."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Half hour."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Hmm, Virgil thought, something might have happened. As it turned out, something had, just not what he thought. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley leaned away from him in the booth and said, "I was in the Yellow Dog and Bill asked, 'How's Virgil?' He… sorta knows. Not for sure."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So what?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'd rather he didn't," she said. "So, I want people to see me walking out of here, without you, and you going down to your room by yourself."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's really cold and lonesome," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Now, don't worry, Virgil. I'm going to drive home, and I'm going to take my oldest boy's car, and I'll be back," Coakley said. "Now, there's some old friends of mine, sitting up at the end, and I'm going to get up and leave, and stop and talk to them about the case, and you can go by and say, 'See you tomorrow,' and leave. Like, really cool-like."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't think that'll work," Virgil said. "The town's too small."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It might not totally work, but it'll confuse them," she said. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She was back in an hour, satisfied that everybody was confused. "I told my son that we were working a surveillance," she said, as she pulled her sweater over her head and shook out her hair. "So. Tell me about Omaha."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He told her, and she said, "Too bad. So we stay local."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Looks like."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You know what we could have done? We could have mailed one of those pictures of Rouse to ourselves. An anonymous tip. Then we raid the place-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That would involve some heavy-duty lying in court," Virgil said. "I'm up for an occasional breaking-and-entering, but serious perjury…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She nodded. "Good. I agree."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Just checking?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, God, I don't know," she said. "Ever since I started thinking about it, I've had all kinds of ideas, most of them bad. But I can't stop thinking. It's like a disease."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil was sitting on the bed, and he reached over and caught her by the belt, pulled her close, and began unbuckling it, and she scratched his scalp with her fingernails, and said, "Schickel and Brown were all over the west end of the county today, but they didn't get much. I'm sure the rumors are starting to spread, though."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil dropped her jeans to her ankles, and she stepped out of them, and he stroked her thighs with his fingertips. "I do have one idea. But it's probably crazier than anything you've thought of."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tell me about it," she said. "Later." \\\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Later, he said, "Birdy has been gone for eight or nine years. The World of Spirit people threatened her, but they've got no idea of where she might be."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley sat up and said, "Virgil, you can't tell them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, I don't want to do that. For one thing, she's in Nebraska, and we don't have the resources there to cover her. But. She has a twin sister here in Minnesota, and the twin looks exactly like her, and sounds like her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Virgil, jeez…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'd tell her about it," Virgil said. "Go up there and explain what we're trying to do. Maybe Birdy can't get involved, but maybe her sister would be willing to. We put her in a house where we can give her good cover, get a phone. She calls Roland Olms, says, 'Virgil Flowers was here and he's investigating a murder of some kind. Kelly Baker. He says if I don't talk about the church, they're going to indict me, too, as an accessory. What should I do? I'm really scared.' Then we cover her, and see who shows up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She'll tell them where she's at?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No-but they'll have her phone number," Virgil said. "We'll make sure she's in a reverse directory, that they can look her up."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That sounds complicated."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If we can talk her into it, it'd only take a couple days to set up," Virgil said. "We've got a house where we stash witnesses, up in Burnsville; it's empty right now. We could do it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let's try to think of something better than that," she said. "I mean, I think it's unlikely that she'd even go along with it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil got up in the morning, still a little worn from the long drive the day before, and headed in to the Yellow Dog. Coakley was already there, eating pancakes, and Jacoby came over with a menu and asked, "Anything new?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nah. I'm thinking about heading out," Virgil said. "Short stack of blueberry pancakes, Diet Coke."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So she's gonna get away with it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We don't know that, Bill," Coakley said, her voice crisp. "We don't actually know that she did anything."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, Jesus, that just isn't right," Jacoby said. He wandered off to talk with the cook.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked Coakley, "Did you think about it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not much," she said. "My brains were banged too loose."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nasty expression," Virgil said. "Nasty."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I heard it from you," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But women aren't supposed to use it," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Pig," she said. "Anyway, it seems to me to be too crazy. We should be able to figure out things here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That Loewe guy," Virgil said. "We got him scared. He's been stewing for a while-let's go back. Right after breakfast. Let on that we know more than we do, see if he'll cave."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's a plan," she said. "We should take Schickel with us, to add to the pressure."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They finished breakfast and Virgil followed her over to the sheriff's office, where they picked up Schickel, who rode with Coakley, Virgil leading in his own truck. When they got to Loewe's place, they knocked for a while, but got no answer.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 No sign of a truck: Virgil looked in the garage and found it empty.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's better'n if it'd been here," Coakley said. "Then I'd have to worry that he was dead in there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Probably just went downtown for something," Schickel said. "We could go talk to his folks, see when he's coming back."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil tracked around to the front porch, nine inches deep in snow, and peered in the front windows. Through the glass, he could see five or six pieces of furniture bagged up with plastic sheeting; he could see just a corner of the kitchen counter, and it was completely bare.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Schickel and Coakley had walked along the driveway so they could see him on the porch, and when Virgil said, "Uh-oh," Coakley called, "What?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think he's gone. It looks like he mothballed the house."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Oh, boy. He can't… Well, I guess he can."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm gonna try to look in another window," Virgil said. He tramped around the house, but the windows were too high. He looked in the garage, found an old wooden stepladder, put it against the kitchen window, and looked through the open blades of the venetian blind. The kitchen was empty-the dinette table cleaned and wrapped in transparent plastic. Schickel had walked away from the house, and walked back and said, "No heat coming out of the chimney."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let's go talk to his folks," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You go ahead and do that," Virgil said. "I'm going to get my camera and take some shots through the window."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What for?" Schickel asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil didn't want to tell the truth-to get you out of the way while I break in-so he said, "Just documenting it. That he ran. Maybe… I doubt it, but it might help get a search warrant."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Schickel shrugged, and Coakley said, "We'll give you a call when we get out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil walked around to her door, as Schickel was getting in the other side, and said, "Rouse."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She nodded.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley backed in a circle and headed out. Virgil got his Nikon from the truck, just in case, recovered the butter knife from under the front seat, and went to work on the kitchen door. In one minute, he decided that the knife wouldn't work; the lock was too new, and the door too tight.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He checked for a key above the door frame, found nothing, checked the adjacent window frame, came up empty, went back to the garage, looked for a key hanging from a nail on one of the exposed studs, found nothing there, and then knocked it off the top of the door frame.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The key worked fine, and he was in. He walked through in thirty seconds: Loewe was gone, no doubt about it. No note, nothing to look at, although there was a room full of cardboard boxes, packed with dishes and other household stuff, covered with a sheet of plastic. Nothing perishable.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The refrigerator and stove were unplugged, the microwave was missing, the water was turned off.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil let himself out, put the key back, and walked around to the front porch, with the Nikon, and took a few shots.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 When he was done, he sat in the truck, waiting, and daydreamed possible ways to get at the photos at the Rouses' place. Had to get them. Had to get just the smallest edge, just enough to get in there.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Maybe lie. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Coakley called and said, "His folks say he decided to take off for the Cities, check out some job possibilities. They don't know exactly where he's staying, and they don't know when he'll be back."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Is that the truth?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't think so. His mother had that 'I've got a secret' look on her face. She was messing with us. Gene thinks so, too."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You want to come up to Sleepy Eye with me?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't think so. I'm going to look for Loewe. Give me a call when you get there, though… I'm still skeptical about the whole idea."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's what we've got," Virgil said. "I'm gonna give it a shot."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 On the way north again, Virgil thought about the idea of using Louise Gordon as bait in a trap: and thought better of the idea of putting her in a BCA witness-protection house. The problem was, the house was in Burnsville, a Twin Cities suburb that was simply too large. They needed a small town, like Sleepy Eye, he thought, so they could spot whoever came in after her.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 That could be handled, he thought: Minnesota had no shortage of small towns, where strangers would be picked up in a minute. Sleepy Eye had thirty-five hundred residents, more or less, the usual clutter of small businesses, including two cafes. Virgil had eaten at Doreen's once before. He stopped at Gordon's house, knocked, found it empty, because she was at work, and went down to Doreen's.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The place was going through the afternoon slump, and there were only two other customers in the place, a couple of older men huddled at one end of the counter, arguing about medical care. Virgil ordered a hamburger and fries, and when they came, showed the waitress his ID and asked, "You know where Louise Gordon works? I just went by her house and there was nobody home."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What's going on with Louise?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nothing, really. I was talking to her night before last, about a person she knew-actually, her sister-and I need to talk to her again. I forgot to ask her where she works."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The woman took another look at his ID, then said, "She's down at Phillips'. The Ace Hardware. She's not in trouble, or nothing?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not at all. I just need to check in with her," Virgil said. And, "You guys got any berry pie?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Five kinds-cherry, blueberry, raspberry, strawberry, and mixed berry."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Put a piece of raspberry on there, too."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Warmed up?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, go ahead."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ice cream?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Might as well," Virgil said. "Long as there's no calories in there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She snorted: the laugh of a woman who'd heard the line six hundred times, and was being polite. "Lucy. That's her name. Louise's sister. Twin sister."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Nice lady, too," Virgil said. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Louise was sorting nuts and bolts into metal bins at the back of the somnambulant hardware store. When Virgil walked in, he could hear two men's voices, working in a small-engine repair shop, then the tink-tink of metal on metal, and when he turned the corner, Louise spotted him, frowned, and asked, "How'd you do that? Find my call?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Lucy called you? Lenore? Birdy?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "As soon as you left," Louise said. "She knew you must've figured it out from my call. I don't call her in three months, and then I do, and you show up the next day."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil bobbed his head and said, "Well, she's right. I followed you down to your friend's house and had the outgoing calls checked the next morning."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I watched to see if anybody was following me," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was over on the street behind your house, so I could see when you got in the garage. I stayed on parallel streets as much as I could, and then, way back."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tricky," she said. She looked at a bunch of nuts in her hand, selected one, and threw it in a bin. "So what do you want now?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I want to tell you a story, and then see if you could help me out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Why should I help you out?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Because you're a good person? Because it'd be a lot more exciting than sorting nuts?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She looked at the nuts in her hand and said, "Let's go get a cup of coffee."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They wound up back at Doreen's, sitting in a booth, and Virgil made his pitch, starting with a couple of questions, spoken quietly. "How much do you know about Lucy's love life? When she was married to Roland?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Enough," she said. "I know about the swapping and so on. And you said that they might be abusing children now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not just now… for a long time. Generations." He told her about Kelly Baker and the evidence of multiple partners, and sadism. He told her about Bobby Tripp, and his murder of Jake Flood.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm not a prude. I've been married and divorced a lot, and I like women a lot-but that's not what we're talking about here," Virgil said. "And this isn't some phonied-up sex ring where there're a bunch of wannabe therapists manipulating the kids… This is hard stuff, with hard evidence. And it may have been going on for a long time. Maybe a hundred years. Their grandparents might have brought it over from Germany with them, a long time ago."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So exactly what do you want me to do?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Lucy won't help, because she doesn't want to have to go to court and testify about her sex life," Virgil said. He didn't mention that Birdy was scared to death. "But: you look exactly like her, and you sound like her, even now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We were always pretty identical. Nobody could tell us apart," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "And they haven't seen her for years. Now. If we put you in a small town a hundred miles from here, if we can get them to bite, if we can get them to threaten you, we can hit them with search warrants. If we can just get inside a couple of their houses, if we can just get the kids by themselves, we can make our case."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if they shoot me?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil grinned and said, "That'd certainly make the case for us."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Her eyebrows went up, and he quickly added, "No, no, no. You'd be covered twenty-four hours a day. That's why I want to stage it in a small town. Have you ever heard of Hayfield?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No. It's in Minnesota?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, it's up north of Austin. I got involved in a missing-kid case up there. People thought a kid had been kidnapped, but he hadn't been-he'd drowned, actually. I mean, a tragedy. But I know a lot of people in town from the investigation. The thing is, we could put you in a house there, and talk to the neighbors, and when anybody unfamiliar went by, we'd get an instant alert. I mean, the town's half as big as Sleepy Eye. Maybe less than half."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "How long would it take?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If they didn't bite in a few days, they wouldn't," Virgil said. "You could just come back here, and be done with it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Would I get paid?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure, we could fix something up. Not a lot, but something."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The thing is, work is really slow right now," she said. "Dave would be happy to see me take a couple of weeks off."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "So. We got a deal?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Better'n sorting nuts," she said. "Or bolts. I'll do it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They talked about it awhile longer, and then Virgil walked her back to the Ace Hardware. "I'll get back to you-but it'll be in the next couple of days. Soon. I've got to run over to Hayfield and set up a house, get some guys to work it with me. Then we'll go for it." Virgil called Coakley: "She'll do it. I've got to call my boss, get his okay, and then I'm going to run over to Hayfield and see if I can find a house. I know an old guy up there who I think will help us out."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Loewe is in the wind," Coakley said. "He sold his truck yesterday up in the Cities, got cash for it. Went right to the bank with the buyer. I called his bank here, and he took everything but five dollars. That's confidential, by the way, I got that on a friendship basis."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think we let him go, for now," Virgil said. "If we said anything publicly…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "That's what I think. You're coming back tonight?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think so. I'll see what happens in Hayfield," he said. "If we're going to do this, we want to do it quick. I keep worrying that somebody will tell them about the young-sex angle, and those pictures go up in smoke."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So we hurry," she said. "We hurry."\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 17\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil headed for Hayfield, and got on the phone with Davenport to tell him what he wanted to do. "I worry about bringing in a civilian," Davenport said. "What if they walk through the door and pop her?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "This isn't about bringing in a civilian-it's about bringing in the only person who could do the job, Birdy's twin," Virgil said. "I'll put her in a vest, but I don't think they'll go right to guns. They'll want to know what she said to me before they do that. I need a couple of guys, though. Del, Shrake, Jenkins, you, I don't care, but at least two."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I can't do it, but I'll get you two. Do you have a house in mind?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah, an old guy named Clay Holley, and some people in his neighborhood. I got to know them pretty good, and I think they'll go for it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "When are you going to make the call?" Davenport asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tomorrow, or the day after, if Holley goes along," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right, I'll see who I can shake free. Stay in touch. And, Virgil… you're sure about this sex thing?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm sure."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If you're so sure, why can't you just file on it, get a search warrant?" Davenport asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "That's a sensitive issue."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 After a moment of silence, Davenport said, "I've had a few issues myself. Good luck with that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Clayton Holley was eighty-nine years old and lived in the perfect house-perfect for a minimum-wage farm woman who'd fled her husband. The house was old and very small, white clapboard, two bedrooms, a narrow living room, a kitchen a little larger than the house deserved, a damp basement that smelled of mildew, rusting tools, sour drains, and clothes-dryer exhaust, along with the slightly musty alcoholic odor from five or six barrels of Concord grape and rhubarb wine that Holley usually had cooking in the basement.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Holley came to the front door when Virgil knocked, adjusted his glasses as he looked through the storm door window, then smiled and said in a frog's croaking voice, "That effin' Flowers, as I live and die." He pushed the storm door open. "Come on in. What the hell are you doing here?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil kicked the snow off his boots and tracked into the living room, and Holley clicked off what looked like a new television and pointed Virgil at one of two purple corduroy La-Z-Boys.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil sat, and said, "You gettin' any?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Holley scratched his crotch and said, "Matter of fact-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay, I don't want to hear about it," Virgil said. "How old is she?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "A nice, crisp sixty-four," Holley said. "She has an orgasm, the neighbors run for the tornado cellars."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Jesus, Clay, she's a child. You've got kids older than she is," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yup. Two of them, anyway," Holley said. "Why are we talking about my sex life? It's not all that interesting."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was hoping you were shacked up with somebody so you could go away for a couple days," Virgil said. "I want to borrow your house. And maybe a few of your friends."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Holley studied him for a moment, then chuckled. "This is gonna be good, isn't it?" \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Holley listened to the story and said, "Marie lives two houses down, so I could stay there-I stay over every once in a while anyway, when I'm too fucked-out to walk back to the house. I'll tell you what, that Viagra stuff can be the curse of old age."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Man, I really don't want to hear about it," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Anyway, we definitely could set up a surveillance system. We've got the Johnsons down on the one corner, and the Johnsons down on the other corner-they're not related-and the Pells, and the Schooners… they're all retired, they've all got cell phones. I can call them up right now, we can meet over at Marie's. She's got the biggest house. These folks'll all go for it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "So you're ready to say 'yes'?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Hell, yes. Goddamn interesting thing you got going here, Virgil," Holley said. "I'll call up the TV and give 'em an interview when you bust everybody. Be a hero."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're welcome to do that-I can even give you a name or two," Virgil said. "All right. Call your friends. Let's see if we can do it tomorrow." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 It all went better than Virgil had any right to hope, he told Coakley later that evening, when he got back to Homestead.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "His girlfriend slapped together a batch of oatmeal cookies, and we got all of these old folks there, having a party, and told them what we wanted to do, and they were all for it," Virgil said. They were back in bed, covers up to their chins. "I called Gordon, and she's up for it. I'll go up there tomorrow, pick her up, truck her ass over to Hayfield. Davenport got me Shrake and Jenkins, a couple of thugs, perfect for this, and they're coming down tomorrow. We'll make the call tomorrow, noon or early afternoon. That'll give Roland time to talk to other people, get organized, and get up there."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think we're putting a lot of weight on the idea that they'll be able to trace the call," Coakley said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Got to," Virgil said. "They wouldn't take any other kind of hook. They've got to work for it. They've all got computers, and it won't take a genius to work the reverse directory. Clay's in there, C. Holley. They'll find it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if they don't come?" Coakley asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well, I'm gonna put a bug in their ear," Virgil said. "I'm gonna go talk to Alma Flood tomorrow, sometime when this weird guy isn't there-the chicken plucker."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Wally Rooney."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah. I'm going to let it slip that we've got information coming, and see if I can squeeze anything out of her. Talk the Bible to her for a while. There's something going on with her; I don't know what. But-I'm gonna let her know that we've got a source, and that we're closing in on them. That'll give them a push."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Can't talk about child sex to her," Coakley said. "Not yet."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Not yet. But I can talk about Kelly Baker, and how she was abused. I can wonder if more church members might have been involved. Leave the impression that I'm ignorant, but learning, and that we have this source-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What do I do?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If we snap the trap on these guys tomorrow evening or the next day, you gotta be ready to get a warrant and hit Rouse," Virgil said. "Rouse is the key. There're a lot of photos-that'll bring down the whole thing. So we snap the trap, if we get one inch of info, from anybody we get, about Rouse, I call you, and you go with all the guys you can get."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Say I believe you when you say they'll track her down. But what if the people who show up aren't the people you know? But she should know? And she goes to the door, and she doesn't know who Roland is-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "She knows Roland," Virgil said. "She saw him a lot, when Lucy was first married. And she can refuse to let him in… unless he's the only one who shows. But I see what you mean."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Best shot would be to take Dennis and Gene with you. They might be able to pick out who they are."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Let's talk to them," Virgil said. "Too late tonight, but first thing in the morning. Damn, this is going to be interesting."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Her hand slipped down his thigh, and groped, and found him, and she sighed and said, "I'm gonna miss you, Virgil."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah? How much?" \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The next day was a rush. Instead of picking up Gordon, which would have been a two-hour detour, he called her and she agreed to drive to Hayfield on her own. She was excited.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "This is a lot better than sorting nuts. I bought a new pair of shoes, I just, uh… I don't know why I did that."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "Take it easy; drive carefully. We don't need you winding up in a ditch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Dennis Brown, the police chief, and Schickel agreed to go, and would drive over together. Virgil told them to take binoculars and be prepared to stay late, and maybe overnight. "We'll pick up a motel tab, if you have to stay over. If they don't come by the second day, they won't be coming."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil was out of the motel at eight o'clock, heading west on I-90, to the Flood place. When he pulled in, one of the girls, dressed in work clothes, came out of the barn and took a look at him; went back in the barn and, a few seconds later, came back out with her sister, who was carrying a basket containing a half-dozen eggs.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Whatcha want?" Edna asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I need to talk to your mother again," Virgil said. "Is Mr. Rooney around?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He's run into town. He'll be back in an hour," Helen said. "Whatcha want him for?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't," Virgil said. "Just wondering if he was around."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The two of them, standing side by side in the snow-covered yard, looked like a black-and-white photo from the 1930s, a couple of orphan girls in a coal town in West Virginia, or out on the prairie in a sod house, or something, drab, colorless clothes, too-fair skin, and pale eyes. And they carried with them the general sense of solemnity he often saw in old photos. Edna said, "Well, Mother's inside. She's been a little off-center, ever since the last time you were here. Maybe got a bug. But we'll go tell her you're here." AND Alma Flood looked like one of the old photos, too, Virgil thought, when the girls took him up to the front room. She was sitting in the same chair, dressed in a long black skirt and a gray shirt with a darker gray cardigan sweater, buttoned almost to the top. The pocket of the sweater showed some wads of toilet tissue; a reading light shone over her shoulder, and she had one finger inserted in her Bible, toward the very end.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What is it this time?" she asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I wanted to talk to you," Virgil said, taking a chair without asking. "I've been trying to settle the whole Kelly Baker murder in my mind. I'm pretty sure I know what happened. I believe your husband and Jim Crocker were involved in a sexual relationship with her, and were present when she died, and that the Tripp boy found out about it. That set him off, and his arrest set off Crocker, and Crocker was killed to keep him quiet."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Impossible to prove all that," she said. "Everybody's dead."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "But proving it, if we could do it, would still be interesting, because there might have been a third man involved, or even more," Virgil said. "Which brings up the whole question of the World of Spirit. All of these people were members, including Kelly and her parents. So the question comes up, was this a church thing? I mean, a regular church thing, allowed and supervised by the church? How many people were involved?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's not the church," she said. "It can't be the church." But she was stressed, and, Virgil thought, maybe lying.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It would be hard to believe," Virgil said. He nodded at her Bible. "Anyone who takes the Bible seriously, who believes that we'll go on to another world, couldn't be involved in this kind of thing. Child abuse, murder. But we know about the problems that the Catholic Church has had… There will be, Mrs. Flood, hell to pay. Literally. You read in your Good Book where John the Revelator says, when he talks about the City that has no need of the Sun, because it has the Light of the Lord. He says, 'There shall in no wise enter into it anything unclean, or he that maketh an abomination and a lie: but only they that are written in the Lamb's book of life.' Will the people in the church enter that City?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She sat as if stricken, didn't say a word, but fixed him with an eye like a dead bird's, not even blinking.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 One of the girls said, "Mom? Are you okay?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "'They repented not of their murders, nor of their sorceries, nor of their fornication, nor of their thefts,'" Virgil said, leaning forward, pounding it in. "And then there's the part that says, 'And I saw, and behold, a pale horse: and he that sat upon him, his name was Death, and Hades followed with him.'"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 No response. One of the girls said, "I think you should go now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil stood and said to Alma Flood, "I've got a source who knows about the church. I spoke to her yesterday, and it's possible that the sins of the church will come back to haunt all of you. Save yourself and your daughters, Mrs. Flood. Help me out, if you can."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Finally, she moved, to shake her head. "You go on now," she said. "Go on out of here."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil turned away, and she said, "Maybe."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Maybe something will happen. Maybe the pale horse is already here." She held up her hand and looked at it in the light of her reading lamp, and said, "You go on. But I will talk to you one more time. Not now." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The two girls came as far as the side door.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Edna said, "Rooney wouldn't like to see you here. He says you have a bad effect on our minds."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said, "I'd like to hear you speak your minds, what you two really think. What you talk about at night, between the two of you. You're old enough to have your own thoughts. Then we could decide whether I'm bad for you, or Rooney is."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Neither one said anything, and Virgil walked away, turning once to see them standing on the porch, watching him. Helen's lips were moving; she was speaking to Edna without looking at her, tracking Virgil instead; or maybe it was a prayer. Virgil was thoroughly creeped out, not only by Alma Flood and the two girls, but by himself.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 There was, he thought, something fundamentally crooked about using the Bible to crack a Bible-believer, and that feeling of being stained by his own actions, if that's what he felt, reached so far back into his childhood that he'd never escape it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He looked back at the house, snarled, "Fuck it," over his shoulder, and headed down the drive. SOMETHING LIKE two hours over to Hayfield, but he made it in a bit more than an hour and a half, by driving way too fast. As Virgil pulled in to the curb in front of Holley's place, a brown Cadillac sedan came around the corner and pulled up behind him. Jenkins and Shrake, the BCA's muscle, got out of Shrake's Cadillac, and Shrake said, "Yet another case he can't handle on his own."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil asked, "You guys bring your guns?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jenkins said, "Oh, shit, I knew we forgot something." He was carrying a canvas bag and he lifted it and said, "Radios."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Shrake was looking at the house and said, "Are we all going to fit in there?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Probably not. Probably only me, I'll be in a bedroom closet, and one more guy, down the basement," Virgil said. "The other guy will be next door, and when the talk stops, you'll come out to the side door. If we need you, you're five steps away."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Couldn't hear-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'll be able to," Virgil said, "and I'll yell." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Louise Gordon, Dennis Brown, and Schickel were sitting in Holley's living room, watching television, with a couple of sacks of Doritos and brown bottles of root beer. Gordon got up when Virgil knocked and came in, and said, "Are we going to do it?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sure, we're good," Virgil said, smiling at her. He introduced Shrake and Jenkins to the others, and asked Gordon, "You study your lines?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yes, I did. But Clayton said they sounded stilted-he used to be in a little theater."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I was pretty good, too," Holley said. "I once played the Nazi in The Sound of Music. That was sort of the high point of my career."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We don't want a play," Virgil began, but Schickel interrupted.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You want an improv," Schickel said. "So we've been practicing, like we're talking on the telephone with her. We got it going."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "All right," Virgil said. "I'll bite. Let's say I'm Roland…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They went through the phone call, and Virgil stopped it a few times and went off in different directions, and she always brought him back, sounding appropriately flustered and, at times, frightened.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Okay, I'm impressed," Virgil said. She was a natural bullshitter. "Let's make the call."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What if he's not home?" Gordon asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Then we make the call later," Virgil said. "Keep making it until he answers. We know he's around the farm, because Sheriff Coakley has seen him."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They made the call and he wasn't home. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They spent the next half hour going around to the neighbors, and talking about where to leave the cars, and deciding who would be doing what; fifteen minutes into the half hour, Gordon called again, and got no answer. At the end of the half hour, as they were all getting back to Holley's, she made a third call and suddenly lit up, and asked, in a hushed voice, "Roland?… This is Lucy. Lucy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They couldn't hear the other end of the conversation, but they could hear the pitch.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon: "I'm a little scared here. I don't know how they tracked me down, but this state agent said if I protect you, then I'm an accomplice. I haven't even been there in forever, and he says that makes no difference. He wants me to testify against you, against the Spirit and Emmett and all them… No, I'm not going to tell you where I'm at. What I'm going to do is, I'm going to get a suitcase and tomorrow morning I'm going to Florida or California or Hawaii or someplace and let you clean up your own messes… I don't want to hear about any money, you sonofabitch; you passed me around like I was a side of beef, you owed me that money and more… But you… I don't care, I'm just telling you. They're coming and you better hide out, because this Flowers guy is going to put you all in prison… I didn't tell him anything, I told him I didn't have anything to tell, but he knows I was lying. Now I'm going, I'm on my way, and I've said what I was going to say, and I only got one more thing to say to you, which is, go fuck yourself."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And she slammed the old-fashioned phone back on the receiver and looked around, a thin veil of sweat on her forehead and upper lip. "How'd I do?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Shrake launched himself out of his chair and said, "Goddamn! That was so amazing, you oughta be in the theater."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Awful good," Virgil said. He was beaming, and he beamed on. "Awful good. Okay, folks, the fire is lit. They couldn't get here in less than a couple hours and probably not less than four or five. I say we order up some pizza and beer, see if we can get a decent movie… Clay's got a Blu-ray."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Party on," Jenkins said. "Goddamn, I like this kind of detectin'. You detect good, Flowers." They got the pizza and beer and soda and a Bruce Willis Die Hard movie about a computer genius; and Holley got a couple of the cooperating neighbors over, and it was a little like an old-fashioned Christmas.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 While that was going on, Virgil took Shrake and Jenkins in the back bedroom and they sat on a bed with a bowl of chips and Virgil said, "If they come, and if they say or do something that we can pop them for, we're going to go straight at them. Read them their rights, but roll right through that, threats, whatever it takes. If they ask for an attorney, we'll tell them that we're taking them up to Ramsey County, and they'll get an attorney there. We ask no more questions, but we talk among ourselves, you know…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We know…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Right at the beginning, even before reading the rights, we break them apart. We've got two bedrooms, the kitchen and living room, the car, however many there are, we isolate them. I'll come and talk to each of them, in turn. I'm looking for one good solid piece of information-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What?" Jenkins asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't know, but I'll know it when I hear it," Virgil said. "I'm looking for something I can use in a search warrant. If I get it, I'm going to take off, and you'll be on your own for moving these people up north. I haven't talked to the sheriff here, but we could probably get a car if we needed it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We can work that out," Jenkins said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I know it's all sort of ramshackle, but I'm in a big hurry, and this is what I've got," Virgil said. TWO HOURS WENT BY, and they moved the cars around the block, scattering them. Jenkins and Virgil stayed in the house with Gordon, while Dennis Brown went to the house on one side of Holley's, Shrake and Schickel to the house on the other side, and Holley went down to his girlfriend's place. Everybody would be watching the street, linked with cell phones and radios.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon started cleaning up after the party, and Jenkins set up a half-dozen wireless microphones, with recording equipment under the bed. Virgil, Jenkins, and Shrake would have headphones to monitor the talk, although Shrake's wouldn't work until he was just outside the house. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 And they waited, watching TV.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They asked one question, two hundred times. "Do you think they looked up the phone number?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil found it hard to believe that they'd be too stupid to do that; that somebody wouldn't do it.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Our big problem is gonna be if they come hat in hand, are polite, say their piece, and leave," Virgil said. "Even if there are some little threats buried in there… you know, 'We'd sure be unhappy, Miz Lucy, to hear you were telling lies about us.' If they go that way, we've got nothing."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They got past three hours, and past four hours, but they didn't get past five hours.\par
\par
\s2 \qc\snext0\b\f0\fs28\fi0\li0\ri0 18\par
\s0 \ql\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0 \par\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They came in a crew-cab pickup, three of them. The first word came from an elderly couple who lived at the end of the block, an excited woman on her cell to Virgil: "Big pickup, not from town, turning the corner like they're lost, looking at house numbers."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil clocked his radio: "Incoming," he said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We got them," Dennis Brown said. "The guy in the driver's seat is Emmett Einstadt Junior. They call him 'Junior.' There are two more, I think, but I can't see who they are. Could be one in the back-that'd make four."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The big Chevy crew cab stopped in front of Holley's house, and a minute later three men climbed out, awkwardly, a little stiff from the ride, and regrouped on the sidewalk.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jenkins hurried across the house and down the stairs into the basement, while Virgil crouched in the front bedroom, looking out through a hole in a venetian blind. Gordon stood behind him, in the doorway, twisting her hands nervously. They had wrapped a woman's bulletproof vest around her, and covered it with a thick quilted housecoat. She still looked a little porky, but with her round face and fleshy hands, not unconvincing.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 A radio beeped, and Virgil said, "Yeah?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "The guy with the black watch cap is Roland Olms, and the third guy-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Wally Rooney," Virgil said. Outside, Rooney had pulled off his baseball cap to scrub at his hair, and then replaced it. "Excellent."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He turned and repeated the information to Gordon, and she repeated it, "Cowboy hat is Junior, the other guy is Wally Rooney, and I know Roland…"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She was almost hyperventilating, and Virgil grinned at her and said, "Take it easy. This isn't as hard as it looks, and it's gonna be interesting. They didn't bring their shooter with them, so I don't think we have to worry about that. You just get out there and argue with them."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "They brought this Rooney man you told me about-do you want me to tell them that you think he's messing with Flood's daughters?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Keep it in mind, and if it comes up, mention it. Don't force anything," Virgil said. "Okay, they're coming up the walk. When the doorbell rings-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Count to five."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Jenkins is right at the bottom of the basement stairs, I'll be right here… Leave the bedroom door open." He was looking out through the blind. "Okay, they're on the porch. Here we go."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 He put the radio to his face and said, "Shrake, as soon as they're inside, and talking, I'll double-click, and you get up by the side door."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Got that," Shrake said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 The doorbell rang, and Virgil stepped over to the bedroom closet and said, "Break a leg," and stepped inside and plugged in the radio earpiece and turned off the speaker. Gordon was headed toward the door and he said into the radio, "Showtime." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon pulled the inside door open and looked through the storm door. Roland Olms was there, and she looked at him and said, aloud, "Oh, no. Go away."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Olms pulled at the storm door handle, got it open, and said, "We need to talk to you, Birdy."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I said everything I was going to say. What if the police are watching? Go away, go away," Gordon said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Olms was just under six feet tall, and thick through the chest. He stepped directly at her and said, at the same time, "We can't do that. We need to talk," and his momentum pushed her back without touching her. She backed into the living room, and Junior Einstadt followed, with Rooney right behind. He pushed the inner door shut with a solid thunk, and they were all standing in a circle.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Roland Olms asked, "You been here the whole time?" and, "You spend all my money?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If this Flowers gets on to you, you won't need any money," Gordon said. "He says you all killed some girl and left her body in a cemetery. Some underage girl, and he's like death on that. He says somebody beat her with a whip, and more than once, more than the time she was killed. He says she was gang-raped-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Wasn't no rape," Einstadt said. "She was glad to get it any way she could."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You were there?" Gordon asked, and her hand went to her mouth.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Didn't say that," Einstadt said. "But it wasn't no rape. She was friendly, and she liked it. She'd get in a pool, and she could get seven or eight of us in one night. More the merrier."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Rooney said, uneasily, "That's not something we ought to talk about."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Why not?" Einstadt said. "Old Birdy here was the same way, hot to get it on."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Was not," Gordon said. "That's why I ran away, you sonofabitch."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They were still standing and she began backing away from them.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Olms said, "I oughta take my money's worth right now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Rooney said, "Shut up, Roll. We're not here to fuck around." He looked at Gordon. "What all did Flowers ask you? We want to know all of it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He said that this dead girl got raped by a bunch of you," Gordon said. "He said that you were all church members, and he wanted to know if the church, you know, made little girls do it."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "He mention anybody?" Rooney asked. Gordon's mouth flapped for a moment, as she tried to decide whether to mention Rouse, and it looked to the three men as though she was trying to avoid saying something, and Rooney pressed: "Did he mention me?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Well… he sorta wanted to know about you and the Flood girls. The girls were just little bitty kids before, I couldn't even remember them, hardly."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Sonofabuck," Rooney said to Einstadt. "He knows."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon said, "He was asking about some other people… the Bakers, a boy named Loewe, I think he was that little queer back then-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Didn't know you knew him," Olms said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I knew who he was; some of the women thought he was queer… and Flowers is telling me all these things. Rouse? Rouse's daughter, riding around with people? Does that mean anything?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Ah, shit," Einstadt said. "Who's talking to him?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I think he's talked to a lot of neighbors."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "If he's asking about the Rouses, we got a problem," Olms said. "Greta Rouse has been serviced by everybody in the Spirit. If they get hold of them-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We gotta get back," Rooney said. "We need a meeting tonight. With everybody. We gotta call Emmett, right now."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt looked at Gordon for a moment, then said, "We got a friend who's going to stay with you overnight. Just to make sure you don't go talking to cops until we can have our meeting."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "You're not staying here," Gordon said. She had pulled enough out of the three men that she expected Virgil to burst into the living room. She wanted to look back toward the open bedroom door, but didn't.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're not. But you remember Kathleen Spooner?" Einstadt asked. "She'll be here in a few minutes. She's gonna stay with you. We don't have time to fuck around, Birdy. So we'll bring Kathleen in, and tomorrow morning, we'll have figured out what we're gonna do, and she'll be gone."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm not-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're not asking," Olms snapped. "We're telling you." And he reached out and slapped her hard, and she staggered and almost fell: still did not look at the bedroom door, although she was now murderously angry, and it showed. Olms smiled at her: "You remember that, don't you?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Fuck you," she hissed, but she moved away from him, her shoulders hunched, one hand up to deflect another slap.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt went to the door and waved at the truck, and Gordon wondered where Virgil was. VIRGIL, in the closet, clicked the radio a couple of times, which meant, "Wait." Gordon had gotten more out of the men than he could have hoped for. But with Spooner-he wanted Spooner, too. \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner came across the porch steps and inside. "What?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's worse than we thought," Rooney said. "We need to call a general meeting and get back. You've got to babysit."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner showed her teeth to Gordon: "I can do that. We'll get along fine."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I don't want you here," Gordon said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Tough shit," Spooner said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Einstadt said to Spooner, "You know what we talked about. The Flowers guy is all over her."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner nodded and said, "Okay."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We're going," Rooney said, and they tramped out, and as he went through the door, Olms turned and said, "You never were any good." \par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They were gone, Einstadt pulling the door shut behind him, and still no Virgil.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon faced Spooner and said, "I don't want you here. And to tell you the truth, when those men are gone, I'm going to throw you out of here. You might as well go peacefully… you're just making me madder and madder."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner said, "We're just going to sit down and relax for a while."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "No, we're not. I'm telling you-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon took a step forward and Spooner lifted a hand out of her jacket pocket and showed her a gun, a compact.45. She said, "You're not telling me anything."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon said, "She's got a gun. She's got a gun."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner, confused, asked, "Who're you talking to?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 From the front bedroom door, Virgil said, "Me. I'm aiming a pistol at your head, Miz Spooner. If you even start to move the gun, I'm going to kill you."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 From the kitchen door, Jenkins said, "And if he misses, I won't."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Spooner stood stricken for a minute, then realized, and said, "Oh, my God."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "It's all done," Virgil said. "Stoop down, lay the gun on the floor, and then we need to talk. You've still got a chance."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 She put the gun on the floor and stood up, and Virgil and Jenkins moved her to a wall and patted her down, and Jenkins put the cuffs on. Spooner said to Gordon, "Birdy, how could you-"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Eh, not Birdy," Gordon said, with a smile. "You can refer to me as Louise."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil put his arm around Gordon's shoulder and gave her a squeeze. "You were so good."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Jenkins said, "You were so good you made me laugh."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Shrake came in the side door and asked, "Are we taking them on the highway?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "We gotta figure that out," Virgil said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Shrake said to Gordon, "You can work with me anytime. That was prime rib."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Gordon was pleased and flustered, and said, "I missed my calling. I should have been a cop." BROWN AND SCHICKEL came in, and then Holley and his girlfriend, and the BCA agents moved Spooner to a bedroom, sat her on a bed, and read her rights, and then Virgil said, "If you want an attorney, we won't say another word to you until you have one. That's because by the time you get an attorney, everything will have broken open, and you'll have nothing to give us. At this point, I think a jury will listen to those tapes and understand that you were here to kill Birdy-Louise-and they'll convict you of killing Crocker. So if you want a little break, we can tell the prosecutor that you were cooperative, or that you weren't. I have three yes-or-no questions, that's all. Do you understand?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I want an attorney," she said.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil said to Shrake, "Move her up to Ramsey County. Murder one, conspiracy to commit murder, conspiracy to commit child abuse, false imprisonment, no bail. Get her a public defender."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Shrake nodded: "Okay. You headed back to Homestead?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "Yeah." To Jenkins: "You better come with me. We may need the help. We'll be rounding up a lot of people."\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "What were the questions?" Spooner asked.\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 Virgil looked at her, then called to Schickel and Brown, "Could you guys come in here for a minute?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They came in, and Virgil said, "She asked for an attorney, and we signed off on her. Now she wants to know what my questions were going to be. We want you to witness this: we're offering to take her to Ramsey County jail and get her a public defender. No pressure. I'm going to ask her the questions, and if she answers, you're witnessing that she's answering voluntarily. Okay?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 They nodded, and Brown asked her, "You want to know the questions?"\par
\s0 \qj\snext0\f1\fs24\b0\i0\fi567\li0\ri0 "I'm not saying I'll answer them," she said.\par
